{"term":"1956","caseName":"British Transport Commission v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1956/247","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 29, 1957 (Part 2)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13157","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dow, you may proceed.","start":0,"stop":22.861,"duration":22.86}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":22.861,"stop":26.004,"duration":3.14},{"text":"I think it would help the Court a little to understand what this thing is all about, before we go any further.","start":26.004,"stop":32.893,"duration":6.89},{"text":"When the Haiti Victory cut through the bow of the Duke of York one night in the English Channel, as you might suppose a lot of people were killed, injured, and lost their property.","start":32.893,"stop":47.986,"duration":15.09},{"text":"Now, you have heard here that a 104 out of the 115 were from other parts of the world, even as far away as Australia, so to let them sue over there if they want to collect anything.","start":47.986,"stop":64.427,"duration":16.44},{"text":"But five out of the eight people that died were Americans and they constitute the bulk of these claims.","start":64.427,"stop":74.561,"duration":10.13},{"text":"Now, it would also help if we knew just what happens in Europe, when you have limitation of liability.","start":74.561,"stop":84.904,"duration":10.34},{"text":"You don't have it as a label on the first proceeding as you often do here, it comes afterwards.","start":84.904,"stop":94.392,"duration":9.49},{"text":"The first thing you do, everyone's who's everybody else, just as we usually do here.","start":94.392,"stop":101.029,"duration":6.64},{"text":"And after there are suits, and cross-claims, and counterclaims, the Court decides the issue of liability and determines under their rules just who was liable and to what extent.","start":101.029,"stop":114.327,"duration":13.3},{"text":"After that is completed, the ship owner looks at the Bill that's presented to him and then decide whether or not he's going to limit, which is a sensible thing to do.","start":114.327,"stop":126.071,"duration":11.74},{"text":"I think in a sense, we have the cart before the horse here very often.","start":126.071,"stop":130.838,"duration":4.77},{"text":"But we overcome that by frequently using limitation of liability as a defense like under the Jahncke and that case stands for the proposition that you can use it either way and I submit that there isn't a slightest doubt that British Transport can limit now if it wants to, because for the first time there are claims against it.","start":130.838,"stop":153.998,"duration":23.16},{"text":"There weren't before.","start":153.998,"stop":157.444,"duration":3.45},{"text":"Now, the difficultly here originally arose because of the fact that there was a Government involved and a British vessel which our Government thought was likewise a British Government ship.","start":157.444,"stop":173.236,"duration":15.79},{"text":"So they thought it came under the Knock-for-Knock Agreement.","start":173.236,"stop":176.913,"duration":3.68},{"text":"Consequently, there were some confusion and the thing didn't proceed exactly as an ordinary case of this kind would proceed.","start":176.913,"stop":187.445,"duration":10.53},{"text":"Ordinarily, they would have waited until the vessel got where she was going, the Brooklyn Navy Yard for repairs and then British Transport's counsel whose office was there would've label it.","start":187.445,"stop":199.421,"duration":11.98},{"text":"The Government would've come back and answered limited, and claimed against the British for their damages.","start":199.421,"stop":212.083,"duration":12.66},{"text":"We would've come in.","start":212.083,"stop":213.659,"duration":1.58},{"text":"And I only represent the people that were injured, killed and, lost there baggage.","start":213.659,"stop":219.422,"duration":5.76},{"text":"Mr. Doub will speak for the Government's aspect of the case.","start":219.422,"stop":223.245,"duration":3.82},{"text":"So we would've then come in and filed our claims.","start":223.245,"stop":229.318,"duration":6.07},{"text":"And under Rule 43, we'd file them against anybody.","start":229.318,"stop":233.84,"duration":4.52},{"text":"Now, we don't have any admiralty, the equivalent of Rule 13 (g) of the civil rules.","start":233.84,"stop":240.98,"duration":7.14},{"text":"So, for one to have a better, we used Rule 56 or sometimes 54 and have for 75 years.","start":240.98,"stop":248.937,"duration":7.96},{"text":"It goes back, it used to be Rule 59.","start":248.937,"stop":252.262,"duration":3.32},{"text":"At first, as the petitioner pointed out, yes, it was designed for collision.","start":252.262,"stop":259.793,"duration":7.53},{"text":"But it was quickly spread to cargo and then to all sorts of things.","start":259.793,"stop":264.816,"duration":5.02},{"text":"Now, if we had the European and British system of determining liability before we determine whether or not we were going to limit, we wouldn't require the equivalent of Rule 56 or -- or its -- its liberal use.","start":264.816,"stop":282.481,"duration":17.67},{"text":"Who wouldn't need it?","start":282.481,"stop":284.404,"duration":1.92},{"text":"Because all that would be done under the -- under perhaps a very clear rules permitting implead or in cross-libel.","start":284.404,"stop":293.213,"duration":8.81},{"text":"But just assume as we have, as I say, the cart before the horse, we have to use Rule 56 rather liberally in order to get all people before the Court, have a concourse of claims, determine liability all around and then apportion whatever is before the Court for apportionment.","start":293.213,"stop":314.565,"duration":21.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If you have the English system --","start":314.565,"stop":316.478,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":316.478,"stop":317.058,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of limitation, as you put it to us, how would you be able to proceed in this country against the British Commission?","start":317.058,"stop":329.068,"duration":12.01}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We would have to libel a British vessel in England.","start":329.068,"stop":332.574,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you mean you'd have to go to England?","start":332.574,"stop":334.22,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":334.22,"stop":335.573,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that --","start":335.573,"stop":335.851,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We would.","start":335.851,"stop":336.39,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's what the controversy is about, isn't it?","start":336.39,"stop":338.782,"duration":2.39},{"text":"Whether you should go there or be able to do this here.","start":338.782,"stop":342.328,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, they chose to come here.","start":342.328,"stop":344.163,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I understand that --","start":344.163,"stop":344.93,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's no reason to prejudice these people.","start":344.93,"stop":347.015,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm not meaning to decide the case but I can assure you, I'm just suggesting that if you invoke the English system, it carries with it the fact you couldn't have done this under the English system because you wouldn't have the Commission here.","start":347.015,"stop":364.015,"duration":17}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the English system, Your Honor, everybody would've had to go -- if we went to England, everybody would of course had to go to England.","start":364.015,"stop":370.228,"duration":6.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Except the United States could limit its liability or idea in Norfolk as it is.","start":370.228,"stop":375.306,"duration":5.08}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct and the United States did limit its liability here in Norfolk and I think the reason was because Norfolk was up to date and at that time both southern and eastern were five years behind, and it was a prudent thing to do.","start":375.306,"stop":390.7,"duration":15.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And if the British Commission hadn't come here, you would've been helpless.","start":390.7,"stop":393.499,"duration":2.8},{"text":"You'll have to go over there.","start":393.499,"stop":395.857,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if the British didn't come here, then it would be a res judicata over there.","start":395.857,"stop":403.537,"duration":7.68},{"text":"Now, and they would've had -- not a leg to stand on --","start":403.537,"stop":408.461,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The determination --","start":408.461,"stop":408.635,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but they came over here --","start":408.635,"stop":409.561,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of fault -- the determination of fault would've been (Voice Overlap) --","start":409.561,"stop":413.762,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"To determine the fault, yes.","start":413.762,"stop":415.805,"duration":2.04},{"text":"And that's what they came over here to do.","start":415.805,"stop":417.997,"duration":2.19},{"text":"And they said in their pleadings, the United States is -- is not blamed (Voice Overlap) --","start":417.997,"stop":422.308,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But that isn't challenged -- but that isn't challenged, Mr. Dow.","start":422.308,"stop":425.165,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":425.165,"stop":425.904,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not challenged that it would be a res judicata as to fault.","start":425.904,"stop":430.158,"duration":4.25},{"text":"As I understood the argument, that is not a challenged.","start":430.158,"stop":434.794,"duration":4.64}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":434.794,"stop":435.436,"duration":0.64},{"text":"And when you read the fine print on the back of the tickets it's res judicata just about everything else, too, only in reverse.","start":435.436,"stop":443.301,"duration":7.87},{"text":"These people have no claims in England for the most part.","start":443.301,"stop":447.091,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean you -- they couldn't recover because the limitations -- the contract of limitations are respected by their courts?","start":447.091,"stop":454.128,"duration":7.04}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right and they are.","start":454.128,"stop":455.706,"duration":1.58},{"text":"It's against public policy over here, but it's all right over there, and they respect it.","start":455.706,"stop":460.76,"duration":5.05},{"text":"The shipowner is still in the driver's seat over there.","start":460.76,"stop":463.421,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's their concern, not ours.","start":463.421,"stop":465.36,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, but it's these people's concern right here in this Court now, and if were going to have a complete adjudication of this whole controversy in one lawsuit as Chief Justice Taft and subsequently Chief Justice Hughes said in both the case against the Southern Pacific and the -- the Just and Chambers, then it's got to be done here and it's got to be done in one litigation that if you can litigate this thing's a piecemeal all over the world, then there's -- there's nothing.","start":465.36,"stop":502.93,"duration":37.57},{"text":"The British had nothing to lose coming over here.","start":502.93,"stop":505.864,"duration":2.93},{"text":"They came over with fishhooks in their pockets in an asbestos suit.","start":505.864,"stop":509.892,"duration":4.03},{"text":"And they said, we want every bit of that million and a half that we can get, and we deny any liability.","start":509.892,"stop":517.74,"duration":7.85},{"text":"And you America are 100% at fault and the Court says you're mistaken there, you're 100% at fault.","start":517.74,"stop":525.195,"duration":7.46},{"text":"And then, as my opponents said that the money is returned to the Government and the matter is finished.","start":525.195,"stop":532.702,"duration":7.51},{"text":"Well, within that, I find how do you do.","start":532.702,"stop":534.719,"duration":2.02},{"text":"It isn't finished, there's 115 people that hasn't gotten a nickel, and this was the only they're going to get it.","start":534.719,"stop":544.88,"duration":10.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you a question?","start":544.88,"stop":545.936,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":545.936,"stop":547.139,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I was just about to ask you, do you ever think that question was asked about something you had said?","start":547.139,"stop":553.334,"duration":6.19},{"text":"Do I understand from you that the only way this could be justified is the use or under Rule 56?","start":553.334,"stop":564.772,"duration":11.44}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it's -- it's --","start":564.772,"stop":568.267,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Are those rules exhausted?","start":568.267,"stop":570.432,"duration":2.16},{"text":"Does that mean that --","start":570.432,"stop":571.152,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"As --","start":571.152,"stop":571.677,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- no -- no power left in admiralty to sanction its rules as it goes along in connection with this sign?","start":571.677,"stop":581.506,"duration":9.83}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's a very good question.","start":581.506,"stop":583.657,"duration":2.15},{"text":"Mr. Leavenworth Colby of the Government's Admiralty Office, which is one of the finest in the country, has often said that while our civil rules are suppose to be all inclusive and tell everybody exactly what they can and cannot do, the Admiralty Rules as -- as annunciated by Mr. Justice Bradley when he said at the end of his opinion in Scotland, I believe it was, we will now -- at the conclusion of this case, we will announce a few rules and that's just what that they did.","start":583.657,"stop":618.385,"duration":34.73},{"text":"The Admiralty Rules were always a few loose general rules with the District Courts having a right to author those Rules within the framework of the general rules expressed by this Court.","start":618.385,"stop":634.551,"duration":16.17},{"text":"Consequently, we have never attempted in admiralty to delineate by rule every single thing that could or could not be done.","start":634.551,"stop":643.863,"duration":9.31},{"text":"Now, the -- the foolishness of trying to do such a thing is apparent, no two admiralty collisions are alike, there's no such thing.","start":643.863,"stop":654.807,"duration":10.94},{"text":"For -- every collision has different people, different cargo interest, different types of injuries, they can be three, four, five, ten parties mixed up in it.","start":654.807,"stop":664.044,"duration":9.24},{"text":"There can be passengers or not.","start":664.044,"stop":667.113,"duration":3.07},{"text":"The -- the -- it can happen in the waters of different parts of the world and with the flags of any nation.","start":667.113,"stop":674.85,"duration":7.74},{"text":"Now, to attempt to have a body of rules that would specifically guide the Courts in every single step that they were to take in every proceeding would be something inexhaustible, it wouldn't work and it couldn't be done.","start":674.85,"stop":693.131,"duration":18.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Did I understand you to say that if you proceeded in England, but because of your ticket provisions, you would not be able to recover against the British Commission there.","start":693.131,"stop":706.001,"duration":12.87},{"text":"But if you sue the British Commission here, those contract provisions under our law will be disregarded and you can recover here whereas you couldn't have done it over there?","start":706.001,"stop":716.624,"duration":10.62}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and that's substantially --","start":716.624,"stop":717.64,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that makes quite a difference, doesn't it?","start":717.64,"stop":719.518,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a tremendous difference.","start":719.518,"stop":720.977,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if it makes quite a tremendous difference to your position as to what -- what -- to scope these limitation proceedings should be given.","start":720.977,"stop":730.748,"duration":9.77}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you are going to narrow the scope of these proceedings to the point where limitation of liability is limitation of liability and nothing more.","start":730.748,"stop":747.175,"duration":16.43},{"text":"And you are not going adjudge the question of fault, or if you do, it doesn't do any good because there's no money there to pay for it.","start":747.175,"stop":758.546,"duration":11.37},{"text":"Then we've got to -- we're in for tremendous overhaul.","start":758.546,"stop":762.767,"duration":4.22},{"text":"When the British came in here -- when the British came in here, they expected to submit themselves to the jurisdiction of this Court which sits in equity for all purposes.","start":762.767,"stop":775.215,"duration":12.45}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's --","start":775.215,"stop":775.456,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":775.456,"stop":775.634,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the whole question in this case.","start":775.634,"stop":776.528,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that -- is that so?","start":776.528,"stop":778.071,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There is --","start":778.071,"stop":778.215,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":778.215,"stop":778.477,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- no question about what they did, the British didn't figure out Rule 56 or what --","start":778.477,"stop":784.729,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But is there in the pleadings or in the record to indicate that they -- they did so consider it?","start":784.729,"stop":791.304,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There is -- there -- Your Honor, I submit there is nothing in the record of any kind or description where the British still hold on to some -- something which will elect them out.","start":791.304,"stop":809.37,"duration":18.07},{"text":"They didn't appear especially for this purpose only.","start":809.37,"stop":812.898,"duration":3.53},{"text":"They did nothing of the sort.","start":812.898,"stop":814.938,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, could they -- would that -- would that -- I asked Mr. Acheson then I ask you, do you think that would make a difference (Voice Overlap) --","start":814.938,"stop":821.095,"duration":6.16}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If they hadn't?","start":821.095,"stop":822.145,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If they say, we appear here only for purpose of limitation and yet they followed always what say you it is.","start":822.145,"stop":827.453,"duration":5.31},{"text":"Would that make a difference?","start":827.453,"stop":828.849,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor --","start":828.849,"stop":829.167,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think --","start":829.167,"stop":829.36,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in that -- in that case, I think the Court --","start":829.36,"stop":831.152,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"We can have it both ways?","start":831.152,"stop":831.77,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- would be justified in striking their appearance from the record.","start":831.77,"stop":834.596,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That if a -- if we'd say -- the Court would say, we won't allow you to appeal.","start":834.596,"stop":838.179,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right because it serves no purpose.","start":838.179,"stop":840.308,"duration":2.13},{"text":"You get -- there's no -- we can't do complete justice.","start":840.308,"stop":843.589,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but complete justice is a big fray from this world, isn't it?","start":843.589,"stop":848.149,"duration":4.56}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what --","start":848.149,"stop":848.549,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It does -- it does --","start":848.549,"stop":848.832,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- this Court used in the -- in the cases telling how this -- this limitation of liability should be -- should be handled.","start":848.832,"stop":855.2,"duration":6.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it does do something.","start":855.2,"stop":856.954,"duration":1.75},{"text":"They are now bound by the finding that the -- the American vessel was not at fault, there were at fault --","start":856.954,"stop":864.337,"duration":7.38}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":864.337,"stop":864.356,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's something, isn't it?","start":864.356,"stop":865.579,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":865.579,"stop":866.545,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And it maybe a good deal.","start":866.545,"stop":868.851,"duration":2.31},{"text":"They can't -- they didn't do anything.","start":868.851,"stop":871.559,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It maybe which?","start":871.559,"stop":872.876,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You cannot say that's it's -- it's an empty thing that to which they subject themselves.","start":872.876,"stop":878.982,"duration":6.11}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course not, I think it's a very important thing that --","start":878.982,"stop":880.896,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":880.896,"stop":881.173,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- they subjected themselves too.","start":881.173,"stop":882.474,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I'm suggesting the -- that that which is clearly adjudicated against them to the extent that -- that this record held is something, isn't it?","start":882.474,"stop":893.816,"duration":11.34}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":893.816,"stop":894.277,"duration":0.46},{"text":"It is.","start":894.277,"stop":894.793,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well and you can't say it's nothing?","start":894.793,"stop":897.664,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dow?","start":897.664,"stop":898.692,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no, I never said it was nothing.","start":898.692,"stop":900.464,"duration":1.77},{"text":"I think it's something that should be enforced.","start":900.464,"stop":903.107,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dow?","start":903.107,"stop":903.183,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If you don't get money from a judgment, you -- what's the use to having it?","start":903.183,"stop":908.266,"duration":5.08},{"text":"Yes, sir?","start":908.266,"stop":908.313,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dow, did you say that if the British Company had not -- the Commission had not appeared in this proceeding, that nevertheless the finding that it was at fault would have been conclusive, parted in the England?","start":908.313,"stop":922.915,"duration":14.6}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think there's any question about it.","start":922.915,"stop":924.812,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then did you also say that if we had the British procedure here of having liability first determined and then --","start":924.812,"stop":939.762,"duration":14.95}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Limitations --","start":939.762,"stop":939.919,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- rather than the cart before the horse, as you described it.","start":939.919,"stop":943.453,"duration":3.53},{"text":"If in that instance there'd been a libel started after the Haiti Victory came back here, not by the British Commission but by American claimants, there could have been in that proceeding a defense by the United States of limitation?","start":943.453,"stop":964.174,"duration":20.72}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":964.174,"stop":965.51,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Would in that instance --","start":965.51,"stop":967.265,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You say a defensive limitation?","start":967.265,"stop":969.124,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, whatever it is --","start":969.124,"stop":970.538,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":970.538,"stop":971.342,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I'm not familiar --","start":971.342,"stop":971.449,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the exact term --","start":971.449,"stop":972.185,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- with the -- I'm not familiar with the chart and whatever it is in any event in that libel proceeding, the United States could have raised the issue of liability of course, could it not?","start":972.185,"stop":984.992,"duration":12.81}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"He had in it's -- in it's --","start":984.992,"stop":986.256,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh no, I'm speaking now --","start":986.256,"stop":986.421,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- limitation of liability petition --","start":986.421,"stop":988.46,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no --","start":988.46,"stop":988.465,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it said you're not liable they --","start":988.465,"stop":989.658,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, hear me out.","start":989.658,"stop":990.778,"duration":1.12},{"text":"Now, what I'm speaking about is if we had the British procedure rather than the one we do of the cart before the horse --","start":990.778,"stop":996.765,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":996.765,"stop":997.983,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I gather that the issue of liability would have been raised on the libel court by perhaps the American claimants against the United States, isn't that right?","start":997.983,"stop":1010.562,"duration":12.58},{"text":"The issue is a liability of the United States.","start":1010.562,"stop":1013.556,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Would have been raised at that time?","start":1013.556,"stop":1014.893,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, would it not?","start":1014.893,"stop":1015.313,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1015.313,"stop":1016.006,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And with the determination in that proceeding that the United States was not liable and even a determination that the British vessel was liable have been binding upon the British Commission that the British Commission did not appear in that libel proceeding?","start":1016.006,"stop":1031.891,"duration":15.89}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1031.891,"stop":1032.326,"duration":0.43},{"text":"I don't think so.","start":1032.326,"stop":1033.076,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Would not?","start":1033.076,"stop":1033.877,"duration":0.8},{"text":"Well then, wasn't the British Commission in a position here where it had to come in to this procedure, allow under our law or else suffer as you told me they would suffer, a binding -- binding upon them in England that they were at fault?","start":1033.877,"stop":1053.546,"duration":19.67}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1067.424,"stop":1053.546,"duration":-13.88},{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":1053.546,"stop":1054.283,"duration":0.74},{"text":"I'm -- I'm afraid I misunderstood you.","start":1054.283,"stop":1056.398,"duration":2.12},{"text":"If our Court found that the British was 100% liable and we were blameless, even though the British didn't come in, they would be bound by that.","start":1056.398,"stop":1067.777,"duration":11.38}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In this proceeding?","start":1067.777,"stop":1069.014,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1069.014,"stop":1069.504,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But now, what about in a proceeding brought by American citizens against the United States after the Haiti Victory came into an American port --","start":1069.504,"stop":1078.257,"duration":8.75}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1078.257,"stop":1078.863,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in which proceeding the British Commission did not appear.","start":1078.863,"stop":1082.345,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1082.345,"stop":1083.368,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What would be the effect in England of the finding exonerating the United States?","start":1083.368,"stop":1090.316,"duration":6.95}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think -- still think it would be res judicata if the Court -- if the Court shall decide it.","start":1090.316,"stop":1096.101,"duration":5.79}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though the British Commission didn't go into that libel proceeding that litigate the issue of its own lability at all?","start":1096.101,"stop":1105.826,"duration":9.72}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- the people who were injured will make -- would make their own allegations of liability on the part of someone.","start":1105.826,"stop":1114.45,"duration":8.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would assume with -- when they brought it against the United States, it would be on the part of the United States when they brought the libel proceeding against the United States after the Haiti Victory came into port, wouldn't it?","start":1114.45,"stop":1126.414,"duration":11.96}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1126.414,"stop":1127.489,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, if the British Commission were not a party to that libel proceeding, are you telling me that nevertheless a finding of exonerating the United States and laying the fault to the Duke of York would have been binding in England upon the British Commission?","start":1127.489,"stop":1142.298,"duration":14.81}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we say over here, our courts have said that finding is res judicata.","start":1142.298,"stop":1148.958,"duration":6.66},{"text":"Ordinarily, the courts of -- of the maritime courts of the world respect the findings of our courts.","start":1148.958,"stop":1157.017,"duration":8.06},{"text":"Now, and -- and I'm sure that that would happen.","start":1157.017,"stop":1160.553,"duration":3.54},{"text":"What -- the issue that -- that the petitioner has raised here is even if you will get a judgement against us, a claim against us here and you go over to Europe to enforce it, you may not get anything anyway.","start":1160.553,"stop":1184.165,"duration":23.61},{"text":"Well, it's a threat.","start":1184.165,"stop":1186.153,"duration":1.99},{"text":"It's true, we might not.","start":1186.153,"stop":1188.488,"duration":2.34},{"text":"In many cases, we wouldn't.","start":1188.488,"stop":1191.455,"duration":2.97},{"text":"But the British came into this with the idea, as stated in their pleadings that they were blameless and that the United States were solely at fault.","start":1191.455,"stop":1200.642,"duration":9.19}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but they came in because, as I understand it, they had to come in or suffer the consequences of a determination against them which would be res judicata in England.","start":1200.642,"stop":1210.915,"duration":10.27},{"text":"Is that what you told me?","start":1210.915,"stop":1214.194,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, they had to come in if they were to get any part of the fund.","start":1214.194,"stop":1219.09,"duration":4.9},{"text":"They wanted money.","start":1219.09,"stop":1220.034,"duration":0.94},{"text":"They couldn't get it unless they did come in and they believe that they were entitled.","start":1220.034,"stop":1226.268,"duration":6.23},{"text":"The Court held, otherwise, they were firmly convinced that they were going to get a good part of that money.","start":1226.268,"stop":1236.176,"duration":9.91},{"text":"And when, to their complete astonishment and surprise, and mine as well, they were held solely at fault.","start":1236.176,"stop":1246.374,"duration":10.2},{"text":"Then they said, well under Rule 56, we pick up our marbles and go home, we're through.","start":1246.374,"stop":1253.428,"duration":7.05},{"text":"We don't owe anybody anything because we only came in to claim, as a claimant in this proceeding.","start":1253.428,"stop":1263.138,"duration":9.71},{"text":"We did not subject our self to the jurisdiction, although, the claimants, if they had claims against us.","start":1263.138,"stop":1272.053,"duration":8.92},{"text":"Well, that strikes if -- if the root of everything that limitation of liability is supposed to be, which is a concourse of claims in the settlement to everything in one litigation.","start":1272.053,"stop":1283.193,"duration":11.14}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Incidentally, on these cross-claims, was there any defense interposed by the British Commission at all?","start":1283.193,"stop":1291.682,"duration":8.49}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"None whatsoever --","start":1291.682,"stop":1293.21,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Or (Voice Overlap) --","start":1293.21,"stop":1293.224,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- except that that --","start":1293.224,"stop":1294.586,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that stage of what?","start":1294.586,"stop":1295.142,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- except the defense that --","start":1295.142,"stop":1296.728,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1296.728,"stop":1296.748,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that you couldn't implead them under Rule 56.","start":1296.748,"stop":1299.402,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well is it that we haven't reached that stage if we decide -- determine that it could be impleaded, do they still have an opportunity to impose -- interpose defenses?","start":1299.402,"stop":1308.083,"duration":8.68}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes, of course these people were slick --","start":1308.083,"stop":1311.475,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, could they do (Voice Overlap) --","start":1311.475,"stop":1312.631,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) to this accident.","start":1312.631,"stop":1313.661,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They do you say?","start":1313.661,"stop":1317.009,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If there is a defense.","start":1317.009,"stop":1318.305,"duration":1.3},{"text":"If these people in anyway contributed to their -- to their own death (Voice Overlap) --","start":1318.305,"stop":1322.83,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then what about -- what about the contract stipulation on the ticket, may that be interposed as a defense?","start":1322.83,"stop":1329.117,"duration":6.29}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Can over there.","start":1329.117,"stop":1330.235,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, can they here?","start":1330.235,"stop":1330.461,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not here.","start":1330.461,"stop":1331.303,"duration":0.84},{"text":"No, sir, it's against public policy here.","start":1331.303,"stop":1333.915,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean it's against public policy if we adjudicated claim against England on that English contract to recognize the law of England in finding as -- is that before us here?","start":1333.915,"stop":1345.092,"duration":11.18},{"text":"Why do we have to decide that?","start":1345.092,"stop":1347.246,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't.","start":1347.246,"stop":1348.479,"duration":1.23},{"text":"I say the --","start":1348.479,"stop":1348.683,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Why don't they investigate?","start":1348.683,"stop":1350.343,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If these people had to take their tickets and their claims to England and sue the British Transport Commission there, most of them would be out of court.","start":1350.343,"stop":1358.256,"duration":7.91}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And you say that's because there's a valid contract in England, so they recognized that the valid contract and you say that if it's -- we tried over here, we tried on to our law --","start":1358.256,"stop":1371.509,"duration":13.25}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so.","start":1371.509,"stop":1371.613,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the law of the United States, which is to permit the United States, would be against public policy?","start":1371.613,"stop":1376.774,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1376.774,"stop":1377.621,"duration":0.85},{"text":"I don't think we will -- we would enforce a --","start":1377.621,"stop":1379.861,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that have been --","start":1379.861,"stop":1380.355,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- a contract.","start":1380.355,"stop":1381.047,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It haven't yet been decided as that would have to be decided, wouldn't it, it's either there or here?","start":1381.047,"stop":1389.225,"duration":8.18}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I had always --","start":1389.225,"stop":1389.977,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) we have a right to setup as a defense that it was governed by the laws of England or wherever it's tried.","start":1389.977,"stop":1395.594,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- yes sir, but I had always thought that any -- any contract provision of that contract that was against public policy in this country would not be given effect in this country if it were used as a defense.","start":1395.594,"stop":1410.726,"duration":15.13}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless sometimes it will say yes or sometimes it's not.","start":1410.726,"stop":1414.112,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I had -- I had thought it was quite --","start":1414.112,"stop":1414.747,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":1414.747,"stop":1416.244,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- quite clear.","start":1416.244,"stop":1416.79,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- always, isn't it?","start":1416.79,"stop":1418.77,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You see this -- this thing was never have occurred, none of these things would have happened if the British Transport Commission had libel this American ship.","start":1418.77,"stop":1432.094,"duration":13.32},{"text":"But believing that that was going to happen in New York and preferring to have it done in Norfolk, they limited Norfolk, then not -- not having a claim against the British ship because believing it was knock-for-knock, they may have not.","start":1432.094,"stop":1451.993,"duration":19.9},{"text":"And as a consequence, it stood solely as a limitation proceeding, although, each party claims that the other was to blame.","start":1451.993,"stop":1460.297,"duration":8.3}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Were these contracts made in England?","start":1460.297,"stop":1462.594,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they were -- most of them made in Holland.","start":1462.594,"stop":1464.417,"duration":1.82},{"text":"The ship was in route from Holland to England.","start":1464.417,"stop":1467.62,"duration":3.2},{"text":"It was a British --","start":1467.62,"stop":1467.887,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and you made a rather -- presented a rather strong point the other side of the -- where they are arguing that they -- they would lose valuable rights which they are entitled to under the laws of their country, they should be tried over here instead of over there.","start":1467.887,"stop":1485.666,"duration":17.78},{"text":"If -- if what you say is correct, whether it would be decided in the case or not, it is certainly true that they can show a very substantial loss to them -- themselves and that this country would refuse to recognize the obligation between them and the people who were there which would be binding over there.","start":1485.666,"stop":1508.459,"duration":22.79}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":1508.459,"stop":1509.088,"duration":0.63},{"text":"As a matter of fact, these people couldn't afford to.","start":1509.088,"stop":1511.712,"duration":2.62},{"text":"They're scattered all over the world.","start":1511.712,"stop":1514.397,"duration":2.68},{"text":"The -- these people can very -- you look forward to -- they're all here now represented by eight American firms of attorneys.","start":1514.397,"stop":1525.024,"duration":10.63},{"text":"If they all had to go to York and finance a case over there, the situation would be impossible for the most --","start":1525.024,"stop":1534.606,"duration":9.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I understand that --","start":1534.606,"stop":1535.362,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that they wouldn't get a cent.","start":1535.362,"stop":1535.856,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's an argument -- that's an argument on your side.","start":1535.856,"stop":1538.611,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1538.611,"stop":1538.981,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But it seems to me like if what you're saying that it being definitely subtle that this country will not recognize the contract which is binding in the country where it was made, that you're giving a pretty strong argument to the other side for the -- for the equities of the situation.","start":1538.981,"stop":1556.955,"duration":17.97}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it -- it would seem so, Your Honor, I know.","start":1556.955,"stop":1560.752,"duration":3.8},{"text":"It would seem so.","start":1560.752,"stop":1561.902,"duration":1.15},{"text":"But actually, I don't believe that -- that that's the case.","start":1561.902,"stop":1566.773,"duration":4.87},{"text":"I didn't mean to be so -- so firm that there's no question about that at all.","start":1566.773,"stop":1570.949,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But don't we have to consider the implications of the rule when we come to construe it, we can't construe the rule, something existing up in air?","start":1570.949,"stop":1580.022,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I want you to construe the implications because the implications of Rule 56, running all through the cases for the last 75 years, make it clear beyond for adventure of the doubt that you cannot take little distinctions and the few little cases here, magnify them into differences that will destroy the effect.","start":1580.022,"stop":1601.429,"duration":21.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I understand that argument.","start":1601.429,"stop":1605.247,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I --","start":1605.247,"stop":1605.385,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you -- do you agree, Mr. Dow, that the rule as written doesn't cover this kind of a claim?","start":1605.385,"stop":1611.889,"duration":6.5},{"text":"You can't rely on the rule itself.","start":1611.889,"stop":1613.944,"duration":2.06},{"text":"In other words, can you --","start":1613.944,"stop":1615.05,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The rule --","start":1615.05,"stop":1615.236,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- directly rely on some inherent power of the court to fashion rules as they go along?","start":1615.236,"stop":1620.623,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1620.623,"stop":1621.143,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you agree with that?","start":1621.143,"stop":1622.135,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely.","start":1622.135,"stop":1622.75,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What s the rule for?","start":1622.75,"stop":1623.316,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the rule doesn't forbid this, neither does it authorize.","start":1623.316,"stop":1626.812,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the purpose of the rule, Mr. Dow?","start":1626.812,"stop":1628.55,"duration":1.74},{"text":"Why was it formulated?","start":1628.55,"stop":1631.745,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in a general way, to bring in -- to be -- to enable the party to bring in all those who were directly concerned with the case itself.","start":1631.745,"stop":1646.825,"duration":15.08},{"text":"Bring them in and do complete justice in one -- in one piece of litigation.","start":1646.825,"stop":1653.796,"duration":6.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But the rule doesn't relate to limitations suits, does it?","start":1653.796,"stop":1657.625,"duration":3.83},{"text":"The rule wasn't a rule enunciated with reference to limitation suits.","start":1657.625,"stop":1661.392,"duration":3.77},{"text":"And when it comes to limitation suit, there you haven't got a general admiralty doctrine, you have a legislatively formulated doctrine with limitations and rights.","start":1661.392,"stop":1671.76,"duration":10.37},{"text":"And therefore, you have to go to legislation.(Voice Overlap) --","start":1671.76,"stop":1674.841,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, that doesn't apply to Rule 56.","start":1674.841,"stop":1678.172,"duration":3.33},{"text":"Judge (Voice Overlap) --","start":1678.172,"stop":1678.502,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Therefore, it becomes important to see whether Rule 56 applies to a -- to a limitation proceeding, doesn't it?","start":1678.502,"stop":1686.69,"duration":8.19}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Judge -- I -- I find it hard to answer that, expect in this way, Your Honor, Judge Brown permitted a cross-claim -- cross-libels in a collision proceeding.","start":1686.69,"stop":1699.601,"duration":12.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not a limitation proceeding, is that right?","start":1699.601,"stop":1704.356,"duration":4.75},{"text":"It wasn't a limitation proceeding, that's just -- all one has to do is to go to Judge Brown's opinion, it's clearly not a limitation proceeding.","start":1704.356,"stop":1709.477,"duration":5.12}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and the rule was formulated to support that opinion, and subsequently extended to other things.","start":1709.477,"stop":1716.122,"duration":6.64},{"text":"And I say that you don't have to extend it to this case, it's also already there.","start":1716.122,"stop":1720.997,"duration":4.88},{"text":"It's there in a dozen ways, not in -- in exactly so that it affords, but almost so.","start":1720.997,"stop":1729.087,"duration":8.09},{"text":"The cases to which -- there's three or four, which would seem to give, and I regret I don't have the time to do it.","start":1729.087,"stop":1734.731,"duration":5.64},{"text":"There's three or four cases like the Algoma case, several others.","start":1734.731,"stop":1738.006,"duration":3.28},{"text":"They would appear to support the petitioner's position here, but an examination of them shows that they do not -- I'm -- I'm sorry, my time is --","start":1738.006,"stop":1747.078,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I understand, Mr. Dow --","start":1747.078,"stop":1747.76,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- so limited.","start":1747.76,"stop":1748.535,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand an argument that relied on the rule.","start":1748.535,"stop":1753.94,"duration":5.4},{"text":"And if so, then one must examine the rule.","start":1753.94,"stop":1756.927,"duration":2.99},{"text":"I understand an argument that says, we're outside the rule, we don't need the rule, we dispense with the rule, irrelevant to this controversy.","start":1756.927,"stop":1767.943,"duration":11.02},{"text":"If that is so, then you're restricted to the limitation statute of 1851 and its amendments, and all the power of the court in enforcing that limitation statute.","start":1767.943,"stop":1779.651,"duration":11.71}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1779.651,"stop":1780.935,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You've got to take one or the other position, as I see it.","start":1780.935,"stop":1784.457,"duration":3.52},{"text":"You can't tell -- take a little bit of the rule and now take a little bit of general equity, and somehow or other see what's equity in the particular case and that's all.","start":1784.457,"stop":1792.993,"duration":8.54}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"This rule, sir, doesn't forbid it -- it doesn't forbid it.","start":1792.993,"stop":1798.141,"duration":5.15},{"text":"It doesn't, in so many words, allow it.","start":1798.141,"stop":1804.023,"duration":5.88},{"text":"But it's the only thing we've have in that in order to achieve this result for all these years and it's done very well.","start":1804.023,"stop":1810.449,"duration":6.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I understood to you say and I can understand the argument that you don't need the -- if the rule weren't there at all, you would make -- we make the same argument for the impleading?","start":1810.449,"stop":1821.637,"duration":11.19},{"text":"Is that right?","start":1821.637,"stop":1821.74,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No question about it.","start":1821.74,"stop":1822.779,"duration":1.04},{"text":"Absolutely.","start":1822.779,"stop":1823.327,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right then you don't look at the rule.","start":1823.327,"stop":1825.256,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dow --","start":1825.256,"stop":1825.559,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But if you look at rule, you got to look at the rules.","start":1825.559,"stop":1828.042,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You say the rules work very well as you interpreted.","start":1828.042,"stop":1831.153,"duration":3.11},{"text":"I understood Mr. Acheson to say that never in the history of the -- of the country has it ever been used in favor of funds, such whether does you --","start":1831.153,"stop":1842.951,"duration":11.8}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm so glad that we might --","start":1842.951,"stop":1844.019,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) and that -- that never had there been a dollar obtained by them.","start":1844.019,"stop":1849.063,"duration":5.04},{"text":"What is your position as to that?","start":1849.063,"stop":1851.439,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Wilbur E. Dow, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Those words were lifted out of context from a decision of Mr. -- Judge Learned Hand in the Algoma case, which I wished I had more time to tell you about.","start":1851.439,"stop":1865.312,"duration":13.87},{"text":"In a case where a petitioner limited, his vessel was gone, he made no claim against anyone.","start":1865.312,"stop":1873.81,"duration":8.5},{"text":"A Canadian seeking to get away from the Canadian $15 a ton limitation, who likewise wanted to limit and limit in the Buffalo Court where he could limit to do and get out of his 15 ton -- $15 a ton Canadian limitation said, \"This man, by limiting is suing me.\"","start":1873.81,"stop":1895.494,"duration":21.68},{"text":"And Judge Learned Hand said, “No, that is not a suit within the terms of this rule.","start":1895.494,"stop":1902.984,"duration":7.49},{"text":"That is not a suit within the terms of this rule and consequently you can't get out of it.","start":1902.984,"stop":1909.005,"duration":6.02},{"text":"And you'll have to limit in Canada where you're supposed to limit.”","start":1909.005,"stop":1914.615,"duration":5.61},{"text":"And then he said -- what he meant was this -- this petitioner in this case cannot get a dollar out of limitation liability proceedings and he couldn't because he wasn't asking for any.","start":1914.615,"stop":1930.114,"duration":15.5},{"text":"You can't get money you don't claim before.","start":1930.114,"stop":1932.948,"duration":2.83},{"text":"That's true of any limitation of liability proceedings that stands all alone and does not involve the Kilkenny cat fight that follows as on the question of liability.","start":1932.948,"stop":1947.022,"duration":14.07},{"text":"And without liberal cross rules back -- cross-claims back and forth, we can't get everybody into the picture and get the concourse of claims, but that's where that expression came from.","start":1947.022,"stop":1966.049,"duration":19.03}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Doub.","start":1966.049,"stop":1967.661,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please -- if the Court please.","start":1967.661,"stop":1969.855,"duration":2.19},{"text":"The artificial scholastic character of the position of the Duke of York is indicative by a number of factors.","start":1969.855,"stop":1980.262,"duration":10.41},{"text":"First, the character of a limitation and exoneration proceeding in an American court.","start":1980.262,"stop":1988.553,"duration":8.29},{"text":"Now, this Court has said that it partakes of a bill for interpleader, a bill to restrain a multiplicity of suits, a creditors bill and I add, and this is never been included in any opinion, but I add a petition for a declaratory judgment of liability because under our system of admiralty limitation procedure, the petitioner is not only attempting to limit his liability, but he his attempting to obtain exoneration, a declaratory judgement that he and his vessel are not liable.","start":1988.553,"stop":2036.982,"duration":48.43},{"text":"Now, what has the -- what is a theory and philosophy of -- of this procedure which this Court has declared?","start":2036.982,"stop":2050.52,"duration":13.54},{"text":"What is the approach that it should take to this problem?","start":2050.52,"stop":2055.606,"duration":5.09},{"text":"Well, Chief Justice Taft said this, as long ago as 1927 in the Hartford Accident Company case he said, “This procedure defines a broad equitable purpose.","start":2055.606,"stop":2073.621,"duration":18.01},{"text":"It should be designed to facilitate a settlement of the whole controversy with all the ease with which rights can be adjusted in equity and that's intended to be given.”","start":2073.621,"stop":2088.206,"duration":14.59},{"text":"He said, “It is the administration of equity in an admiralty court.”","start":2088.206,"stop":2095.087,"duration":6.88},{"text":"He said again, “It looks to a complete and just disposition of a many cornered controversy.","start":2095.087,"stop":2104.348,"duration":9.26},{"text":"To hold, otherwise, would be that unless the petitioner wins, the court does not have the power to administer justice.\"","start":2104.348,"stop":2117.281,"duration":12.93},{"text":"There is nothing in the statute nor in the rules that require so futile a conclusion.","start":2117.281,"stop":2123.541,"duration":6.26},{"text":"Now here, the British Transport Commission as to obtunding that unless he had won in the limitation proceeding, the admiralty court was without power to grant any affirmative relief against it.","start":2123.541,"stop":2139.784,"duration":16.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the case from which you read?","start":2139.784,"stop":2141.76,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I was reading, Mr. Justice Black, in Hartford Accident Company in 1927.","start":2141.76,"stop":2149.626,"duration":7.87},{"text":"And Chief Justice Hughes adopted that language in 1941 in Just against Chambers and those were unanimous opinions.","start":2149.626,"stop":2159.36,"duration":9.73}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Doub, will you -- would you care to say what defenses you think the British Commission could interpose if these courts claims do lie in this proceeding?","start":2159.36,"stop":2169.094,"duration":9.73}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"First, contrary to the brief of our distinguished adversary, they will be able to defend on the ground of limitation of liability.","start":2169.094,"stop":2185.706,"duration":16.61},{"text":"Under the Jahncke case, that's six months limitation to make that defense has been deemed only applicable to an original limitation decision --","start":2185.706,"stop":2199.792,"duration":14.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well now, what --","start":2199.792,"stop":2200.497,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- such as ours.","start":2200.497,"stop":2201.621,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- what about the contract, the ticket contract of limitation?","start":2201.621,"stop":2204.255,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, we know nothing about the ticket business --","start":2204.255,"stop":2207.222,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, whatever it is --","start":2207.222,"stop":2208.051,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I say this -- I say this that my impression was that an American court would apply English law at a contracts made in England but that's merely an impression.","start":2208.051,"stop":2222.865,"duration":14.81},{"text":"I have nothing to do with that corner of the -- of this litigation.","start":2222.865,"stop":2226.817,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But no -- but I (Voice Overlap) --","start":2226.817,"stop":2227.277,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"But suppose (Voice Overlap) --","start":2227.277,"stop":2229.059,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No defenses on the merits in these cross-claims have yet been setup in an answer to the cross-claims or otherwise, have they?","start":2229.059,"stop":2236.406,"duration":7.35}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No, because the District Court denied any standing in the claimants to cross-claim against the British Transport Commission, and in that connection must -- Mr. Justice Brennan, may I point the extent to which this Commission became a party to this proceeding.","start":2236.406,"stop":2258.756,"duration":22.35},{"text":"It didn't merely file a claim.","start":2258.756,"stop":2264.273,"duration":5.52},{"text":"It filed an answer as well as a claim for $1,500,000.","start":2264.273,"stop":2269.748,"duration":5.47},{"text":"It denied the principle allegations of the Government's petition.","start":2269.748,"stop":2274.292,"duration":4.54},{"text":"It denied we were entitled of limitation.","start":2274.292,"stop":2276.962,"duration":2.67},{"text":"It denied we were entitled to exoneration.","start":2276.962,"stop":2281.128,"duration":4.17},{"text":"It asserted -- it put in issue its own negligence.","start":2281.128,"stop":2285.272,"duration":4.14},{"text":"It asserted this collision was attributable solely for the negligence of the Haiti Victory.","start":2285.272,"stop":2291.745,"duration":6.47},{"text":"It denied that the Duke of York was at fault.","start":2291.745,"stop":2296.231,"duration":4.49},{"text":"It litigated that in the same way it would have done so if it had filed a libel against the Haiti Victory and we had cross-libel.","start":2296.231,"stop":2305.787,"duration":9.56},{"text":"The issues were identical and they had to be because in an admiralty collision case, you cannot determine the fault of one vessel without considering the fault of the other.","start":2305.787,"stop":2319.248,"duration":13.46},{"text":"The negligence of each vessel is inseparable.","start":2319.248,"stop":2322.753,"duration":3.51},{"text":"In other words, the subject matter was not merely the fault of the Haiti Victory.","start":2322.753,"stop":2329.81,"duration":7.06},{"text":"The subject matter was the collision, as Justice Learned Hand has said, was the collision.","start":2329.81,"stop":2338.962,"duration":9.15},{"text":"Now, as a matter of fact when the District Court set this case down for hearing in a pretrial order he said, “The issues will be limited to the liability of the Haiti Victory and the liability of the Duke of York.”","start":2338.962,"stop":2356.635,"duration":17.67},{"text":"May it took no exemption to that, as a matter of fact, in their answer when they came in they said, “We accept the jurisdiction of the Court.\"","start":2356.635,"stop":2365.299,"duration":8.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"One thing that puzzles me is how you're up here?","start":2365.299,"stop":2370.202,"duration":4.9},{"text":"As I understand it, the Government had tried to assert a cross-claim or whatever you want to call it against the British, that was never appealed from the -- the denial of that right was never appealed from, is that right?","start":2370.202,"stop":2387.867,"duration":17.66}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Harlan, we did not file a cross-libel or cross-claim explicitly against the Duke of York.","start":2387.867,"stop":2400.837,"duration":12.97},{"text":"And we didn't do it because the United States had an executive agreement with Great Britain which provided that if there was a collision between two vessels, the Great Britain and the United States Government, claims would be waived.","start":2400.837,"stop":2418.355,"duration":17.52},{"text":"We were up -- we believed and our State Department believed that a vessel owned by the British Transport Commission was a public vessel and within that executive agreement, which is known as the Knock for Knock Agreement of 1942.","start":2418.355,"stop":2434.548,"duration":16.19},{"text":"So you'll find references in our pleadings to the fact that this vessel, the Duke York was under that agreement, so we did not feel free to assert a cross-libel.","start":2434.548,"stop":2447.907,"duration":13.36},{"text":"As matter of fact, the State Department will not permit us to do so.","start":2447.907,"stop":2452.066,"duration":4.16},{"text":"The subject was then a matter of considerable representations by the British Government, the -- and the British Embassy, and our State Department, and there were notes back and forth on the subject as to wether their vessel was or was not owned by the British Government.","start":2452.066,"stop":2473.507,"duration":21.44},{"text":"Now, the -- as a result, the question resolved diplomatically until after this case was out of the District Court and on appeal.","start":2473.507,"stop":2483.605,"duration":10.1},{"text":"And then, our State Department acquiesced in the position of the British Government.","start":2483.605,"stop":2489.803,"duration":6.2},{"text":"And in March 1956, we filed a formal cross-claim against the Duke of York in this proceeding which has not been adjudicated.","start":2489.803,"stop":2504.426,"duration":14.62},{"text":"But, Mr. Justice Harlan, we believe that our position to cross-claim is in effect the same as the position of the third party claimants.","start":2504.426,"stop":2521.702,"duration":17.28},{"text":"We think they have more equity than we do.","start":2521.702,"stop":2527.46,"duration":5.76},{"text":"We initiated the proceedings --","start":2527.46,"stop":2528.6,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your -- your position as to the -- as a cross-claimant has never been adjudicated?","start":2528.6,"stop":2534.117,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Neither as theirs.","start":2534.117,"stop":2536.408,"duration":2.29},{"text":"No -- there's been no prejudice to any parties.","start":2536.408,"stop":2538.841,"duration":2.43},{"text":"As a matter of fact, when the District Court ruled that this thirty -- third party claimants could not cross-claim, he had a back rule that we couldn't cross-claim.","start":2538.841,"stop":2549.179,"duration":10.34},{"text":"Because was their position -- we were all parties in our position, that there's no distinction to be made between the two.","start":2549.179,"stop":2555.792,"duration":6.61},{"text":"We're not asking for any preferred position that we have the right to cross-claim, but the third party claimants did not have such a right, legalistically and technically on adopting the kind that --","start":2555.792,"stop":2566.848,"duration":11.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now that --","start":2566.848,"stop":2567.56,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- artificial scholastic reasoning of our distinguished adversary, we might make such a position --","start":2567.56,"stop":2573.548,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now --","start":2573.548,"stop":2573.815,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be --","start":2573.815,"stop":2574.269,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I ask you this question, here is what I'm trying to get straight, maybe I'm confused about it.","start":2574.269,"stop":2579.978,"duration":5.71},{"text":"So far as Mr. Acheson's clients are concerned, they have -- or the other side has been given a right to cross-claim against the British Commission in this proceeding, that's what he's complaining about.","start":2579.978,"stop":2600.875,"duration":20.9}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, by the Court of Appeals --","start":2600.875,"stop":2601.028,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So far as the -- so far as the Government is concerned, you have not had any adjudication below as to your right to cross-claim against the British, right?","start":2601.028,"stop":2614.955,"duration":13.93}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2614.955,"stop":2615.592,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Therefore, it seems to me that you're up there, what sort of an amicus or what?","start":2615.592,"stop":2620.227,"duration":4.63}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you are to consider as that, you can say we're full of traveller, innocent by association but actually, we are a -- one of the principal parties in the District Court and in the Court of Appeals on the merit.","start":2620.227,"stop":2636.436,"duration":16.21},{"text":"But -- but if you feel that's our position, I'd still point out that when you adjudicate the right of the third parties to recover in this proceeding judgements against the British Transport Commission, you will necessarily be adjudicating our right --","start":2636.436,"stop":2655.233,"duration":18.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't -- it doesn't seem to --","start":2655.233,"stop":2656.475,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"I think they're inseparable.","start":2656.475,"stop":2657.294,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't seem to me to follow at all.","start":2657.294,"stop":2659.966,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, not -- I -- I don't mean you -- you would do it deliberately, but I think your (Voice Overlap) --","start":2659.966,"stop":2664.117,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Or as a consequence --","start":2664.117,"stop":2665.013,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- reasoning will inevitably disposed of our finding.","start":2665.013,"stop":2668.306,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's what --","start":2668.306,"stop":2670.923,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"May I merely add this on this point.","start":2670.923,"stop":2673.612,"duration":2.69},{"text":"The United States, as one of largest owners and operators of vessels in the world, if you accept the decision of the Fourth Circuit and the Second Circuit on this question of admiralty procedure, you will be subjecting in the future the United States to the same cross-claim liability when it makes a claim of an admiralty proceed -- limitation proceeding.","start":2673.612,"stop":2702.64,"duration":29.03},{"text":"And it may well be that the liability of the United States will far exceed any financial benefit that we may obtain as a proceeding if we're successful but we are convinced that this is a sound, equitable, fair and just proceeding.","start":2702.64,"stop":2723.047,"duration":20.41},{"text":"And that's our real interest in being here, Mr. Justice Harlan, regardless of any future liabilities on our part or any disadvantage that we may suffer in the future.","start":2723.047,"stop":2734.068,"duration":11.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't suppose -- I've heard arguments like that in connection with the Interstate Commerce Commission and then they found beyond the counter of stand when it came up late to had a reconsideration.","start":2734.068,"stop":2742.861,"duration":8.79},{"text":"I don't suppose you could have stopped the Government by the remarks you just read.","start":2742.861,"stop":2745.381,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- [Laughs] as early as 1868, this Court have a siren, we say determine the underlying principle that's involved here, at least the equitable principle.","start":2745.381,"stop":2760.323,"duration":14.94},{"text":"You held in the siren that although the Government had an absolute sovereign immunity from suit in an admiralty collision case, both in the rem and in personam, where the Government came in and sought judicial relief, its immunity was waived, and the vessel and the proceeds became subject to all claims upon the vessel.","start":2760.323,"stop":2783.046,"duration":22.72},{"text":"And in 1922 in the Western Maid Justice Holmes interpreted your decision in the siren domain, that whenever the United States came into court to enforce a claim, “It would be assumed to submit to just claims of third parties in respect to the same subject matter.\"","start":2783.046,"stop":2806.296,"duration":23.25},{"text":"And in the case of The Thekla, you took a position that the United States became a private suitor and agreed by implication that justice maybe done with regard to the subject matter.","start":2806.296,"stop":2818.689,"duration":12.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You think it makes no difference, the Court of United States or a foreign sovereign, as in the China Bank case, comes in and ask something as a moving plaintiff and where it is brought in -- in a proceeding that has a limited purpose as a willing of the claimant.","start":2818.689,"stop":2840.464,"duration":21.78}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I say, Mr. Justice Frankfurter --","start":2840.464,"stop":2841.646,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no difference.","start":2841.646,"stop":2842.784,"duration":1.14},{"text":"It may be right -- all I'm saying --","start":2842.784,"stop":2843.533,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that that -- if that is a refined distinction.","start":2843.533,"stop":2845.521,"duration":1.99},{"text":"For example --","start":2845.521,"stop":2845.883,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it isn't very refined to say it makes a lot of difference whether you come in to the courts of the United States and say I'm a (Inaudible) I have a -- a great deal.","start":2845.883,"stop":2854.29,"duration":8.41},{"text":"I mean, I believe in the China Bank case very much and where it took an effect --","start":2854.29,"stop":2858.39,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"May I remind you -- may I remind you the language you used, Mr. Justice Frankfurter --","start":2858.39,"stop":2863.458,"duration":5.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I hope --","start":2863.458,"stop":2863.695,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- you said the foreign Government wants our law like any other litigant, but it was their law free from the claims of justice, and that's precisely what the British Transport Commission did here.","start":2863.695,"stop":2874.812,"duration":11.12}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose if the British Transport had -- had won here, below in the District Court, its claim appears on page 24, as I read the record, for a million and half?","start":2874.812,"stop":2889.831,"duration":15.02}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2889.831,"stop":2890.406,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose if million and a half had been awarded then these intervening claimants could've -- could have, without doubt, proceeded in this limitation proceeding against the British Transport, isn't that right?","start":2890.406,"stop":2905.226,"duration":14.82}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, well no -- no.","start":2905.226,"stop":2907.763,"duration":2.54},{"text":"Mr. Justice Douglas, if the British Transport Commission affected a recovery against the United States, it -- it would be because it was not liable, not a fault --","start":2907.763,"stop":2921.933,"duration":14.17}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"This was --","start":2921.933,"stop":2922.009,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- not negligent and we were explicitly negligent.","start":2922.009,"stop":2924.874,"duration":2.86},{"text":"So then the third party claimants would recover against the United States just as the Duke of York did.","start":2924.874,"stop":2932.962,"duration":8.09}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, conceivably, they might have some recovery against the Transport Commission, perhaps not on negligence, but some other --","start":2932.962,"stop":2940.252,"duration":7.29}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think there'd be any -- they would recover against the United States, unless the -- the British Transport -- unless both vessels were held at fault, and the -- in that case the third party claimants would recover against both.","start":2940.252,"stop":2953.753,"duration":13.5},{"text":"I think that might be the situation you were thinking of, but I'm not sure that the contention that's been made by its counsel would mean that it couldn't be -- couldn't even be subjected to any liability here, entitled to all the benefits of our law procedure but not of its disadvantages.","start":2953.753,"stop":2974.287,"duration":20.53}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But I -- I understood that the lower court decisions had gone that far, permit the intervening claimants to file against the -- the party for the limitation proceeding that -- that got the -- its claim of statute with the admiralty.","start":2974.287,"stop":2992.846,"duration":18.56}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Douglas, we're in complete disagreement as to the interpretation of the judicial decisions on this subject.","start":2992.846,"stop":3002.318,"duration":9.47}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's the Steel Inventor case, isn't it?","start":3002.318,"stop":3004.247,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"In the Steel Inventor case, you heard a great deal about what Judge Hough had decided and yet he was reversed by Learned Hand and Augustus Hand in that very case --","start":3004.247,"stop":3014.55,"duration":10.3}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But they -- they allowed the intervening claimants there to proceed against the -- the claim that was -- or the funds so to speak in the hands of the -- of the shipowner who was victorious.","start":3014.55,"stop":3027.469,"duration":12.92}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Let -- let me explain a little more --","start":3027.469,"stop":3028.317,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right?","start":3028.317,"stop":3029.52,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"It's more to it than that.","start":3029.52,"stop":3030.979,"duration":1.46},{"text":"There, a destroyer, the United States Destroyer and the Steel Inventor colliding, the owner of the Steel Inventor sue -- filed a limitation proceeding, just as we did.","start":3030.979,"stop":3044.646,"duration":13.67},{"text":"The United States intervened just as the British Transport Commission did and may decline and look at loss.","start":3044.646,"stop":3055.746,"duration":11.1},{"text":"The United States won in the District Court, lost in the Court of Appeals, the United States was held liable as for the -- its exclusive negligence in causing the act.","start":3055.746,"stop":3067.918,"duration":12.17},{"text":"And we were -- we were a claimant, just as the British Transport Commission.","start":3067.918,"stop":3072.238,"duration":4.32},{"text":"We were held liable for all damages in the case.","start":3072.238,"stop":3076.176,"duration":3.94},{"text":"And yet -- and yet it's been suggested too, there's no authority to hold the British Transport --","start":3076.176,"stop":3081.775,"duration":5.6}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, under -- in the Steel Inventor case, Mr. Doub, were there other claimants as well?","start":3081.775,"stop":3085.899,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":3085.899,"stop":3086.642,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And they also recovered from the United States after (Voice Overlap) --","start":3086.642,"stop":3089.026,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Everybody recovered from us.","start":3089.026,"stop":3091.666,"duration":2.64},{"text":"Now, let me say this too, why in The Adah you had a -- a limitation petition filed by the owner of the scout and Judge Hough held that the accident was solely due to the negligent loading of the stevedore.","start":3091.666,"stop":3110.645,"duration":18.98}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But the United States --","start":3110.645,"stop":3110.903,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"It have held the stevedore liable of course --","start":3110.903,"stop":3112.855,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"The United States --","start":3112.855,"stop":3113.344,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- a claimant.","start":3113.344,"stop":3114.173,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"The United States received an award in the Steel Inventor case.","start":3114.173,"stop":3119.937,"duration":5.76}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Now --","start":3119.937,"stop":3131.085,"duration":11.15}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, don't bother, I --","start":3131.085,"stop":3135.436,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, look at 24 F.2d 657.","start":3135.436,"stop":3139.598,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I did -- already did and I looked at page 24 of your brief, while you say the award to the United States was regarded in the substitute for the (Inaudible).","start":3139.598,"stop":3147.481,"duration":7.88}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -– my doubt here, and I –- I have -- I go into a very more detail in that brief.","start":3147.481,"stop":3155.698,"duration":8.22},{"text":"But there, my note say that the Court held a third party claimants were entitled to recover against the United States, the co-claimant in the Inventor's limitation proceeding.","start":3155.698,"stop":3165.388,"duration":9.69},{"text":"The Court --","start":3165.388,"stop":3165.428,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3165.428,"stop":3165.74,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- said the United States claim the limitation proceedings amounted to a right of suit and admiralty against the Steel Inventor, \"In doing so, it took the position of a private suitor and as to justice be done regarding the subject matter which was a collision.\"","start":3165.74,"stop":3181.248,"duration":15.51}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3181.248,"stop":3185.731,"duration":4.48}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that was the first appeal and on the second appeal, they held Mr. Rosker might think the United States was so here for.","start":3185.731,"stop":3193.922,"duration":8.19},{"text":"Now, you'll find in the City of Boston, the same principle was applied in The Adah in 1919.","start":3193.922,"stop":3201.416,"duration":7.49},{"text":"In Algoma, I'd like to point out what Learned Hand said, he said initially a limitation proceeding is a defensive proceeding but he theorized if there are cross-claims filed against claimants, it may become an offensive action.","start":3201.416,"stop":3223.331,"duration":21.91},{"text":"Now, actually, all we're asking here is that you apply the same kind of efficient, flexible, fair, and equitable procedure that's done every day in an equity reorganization or an equity receivership where there, claimants don't come in, there'll be a discharge --","start":3223.331,"stop":3247.949,"duration":24.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but those --","start":3247.949,"stop":3248.463,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and they won't be able to recover.","start":3248.463,"stop":3249.214,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Those situations are wholly different from what we've got here, except so far as this unadjudicated claim that the Government is concerned, perhaps that -- they bear some analogy into that situation.","start":3249.214,"stop":3261.952,"duration":12.74},{"text":"But those equity receivership places had nothing to do with cross-claims between claimants is easy, nothing.","start":3261.952,"stop":3273.763,"duration":11.81}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that's too extreme statement.","start":3273.763,"stop":3275.954,"duration":2.19},{"text":"Its true, Mr. Justice Harlan, that's its different.","start":3275.954,"stop":3279.323,"duration":3.37},{"text":"It's true that you have a raise that you are distributing among predators.","start":3279.323,"stop":3284.411,"duration":5.09},{"text":"It's true that where the receiver sues a claimant in the proceeding in effects for recovery such as negligent directors and corporate officers, that he is recovering a -- an asset of the State, that's true and that's different.","start":3284.411,"stop":3299.084,"duration":14.67},{"text":"But on the other hand, what I'm emphasizing is that those claimants would have been barred from any participation in the State if they hadn't come in.","start":3299.084,"stop":3314.55,"duration":15.47},{"text":"So there was the same compulsion to come in and I say that in principal -- in principal that the point of view of a court adjudicating all controversies and -- and liquidating them, and disposing of them, and finalizing the situation as just as much equity and as just as much reason for admiralty to take hold here, and do justice and complete it as there is in the equity case.","start":3314.55,"stop":3345.198,"duration":30.65},{"text":"Let me point this out, what if -- if you don't -- from that, this third party claimants to recover here, after -- or the United States for that matter, although, that's not as important frankly because we can always sue on a foreign country and we do it all the time.","start":3345.198,"stop":3364.037,"duration":18.84},{"text":"And it's not -- not the same hardship on us, but what is the punctual -- functional utility of sending these people to England or Holland to litigate further?","start":3364.037,"stop":3379.167,"duration":15.13},{"text":"What's to be served by it?","start":3379.167,"stop":3381.282,"duration":2.12},{"text":"Mr Acheson says “Liability is res judicata.”","start":3381.282,"stop":3385.975,"duration":4.69},{"text":"Well, if that's res judicata, if they're responsibility for the accidents then determine, why in the world shouldn't an American court give these people relief when they came here from all over the world?","start":3385.975,"stop":3399.811,"duration":13.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose you would agree, Mr. Doub, that a ship chandler can -- couldn't intervene in this suit and say now that the British Commission is here, we've got a claim against it.","start":3399.811,"stop":3410.916,"duration":11.11},{"text":"I suppose you --","start":3410.916,"stop":3411.806,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No, those are unrelated claims.","start":3411.806,"stop":3413.449,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Those are unrelated claims?","start":3413.449,"stop":3414.699,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3414.699,"stop":3415.374,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm not sure that in the case of the China case, it would make any difference to me whether it's unrelated or not.","start":3415.374,"stop":3420.685,"duration":5.31}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No, you applied unrelated claim.","start":3420.685,"stop":3422.388,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":3422.388,"stop":3422.989,"duration":0.6},{"text":"Then what's the -- why -- why don't you -- why do you shrink from -- from carrying this to your position of saying they're in Court, they're here, they didn't have to come to the United States but they're here, so we'll lift this claim.","start":3422.989,"stop":3435.65,"duration":12.66},{"text":"Is this admiralty?","start":3435.65,"stop":3437.049,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"That's because admiralty has jurisdiction of this collision and the liabilities arising out of it, and all the (Voice Overlap) --","start":3437.049,"stop":3443.837,"duration":6.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Has a claim in the collision --","start":3443.837,"stop":3445.69,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Or the claim --","start":3445.69,"stop":3446.013,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and the shipowner can claim too.","start":3446.013,"stop":3448.779,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think there'd be a logic in that.","start":3448.779,"stop":3451.324,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":3451.324,"stop":3452.1,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Doub, you -- your associate -- your associate said that the law of this country would be applied to the contracts of those claimants made with the -- with the British vessel.","start":3452.1,"stop":3470.341,"duration":18.24},{"text":"Now, wouldn't they be getting something different here than they would get -- get over in Holland or over in -- in England that they litigated their -- their rights under their contracts?","start":3470.341,"stop":3482.022,"duration":11.68},{"text":"Would we have a different rule of –- of policy here?","start":3482.022,"stop":3486.446,"duration":4.42}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course I don't understand the principle that my colleague annunciated there --","start":3486.446,"stop":3491.151,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":3491.151,"stop":3491.62,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- frankly, I have always -- I have always assumed that --","start":3491.62,"stop":3494.736,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3494.736,"stop":3495.279,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- any court applies the law of the place where the contract was made --","start":3495.279,"stop":3500.544,"duration":5.26}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think so.","start":3500.544,"stop":3500.652,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in determining its validity.","start":3500.652,"stop":3502.302,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3502.302,"stop":3502.968,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"George Cochran Doub","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then --","start":3502.968,"stop":3503.325,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they won't hold you responsible if you don't -- if you don't adhere to that position of course.","start":3503.325,"stop":3511.792,"duration":8.47},{"text":"Mr. Acheson.","start":3511.792,"stop":3513.124,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, am I correct that I have five minutes?","start":3513.124,"stop":3517.919,"duration":4.8}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I think --","start":3517.919,"stop":3518.871,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon, a white light there.","start":3518.871,"stop":3520.903,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Six minutes you have, according to the clerk.","start":3520.903,"stop":3523.168,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That should be.","start":3523.168,"stop":3526.769,"duration":3.6},{"text":"If the Court please.","start":3526.769,"stop":3527.712,"duration":0.94},{"text":"First of all, may I straighten out a few matters.","start":3527.712,"stop":3531.109,"duration":3.4},{"text":"In regard to the discussion that we had a moment ago about my statement that in a 106 years, no dollar had been collected.","start":3531.109,"stop":3540.484,"duration":9.38},{"text":"One of my distinguished opponents thought that I lifted that from Judge Hand.","start":3540.484,"stop":3545.788,"duration":5.3},{"text":"There isn't -- find a man to lift something from that one was lifting.","start":3545.788,"stop":3549.599,"duration":3.81},{"text":"But I was making his statement on my own authority and I was saying that having looked -- I think in every case that's been decided, there is not one where a dollar has been collected.","start":3549.599,"stop":3559.404,"duration":9.8},{"text":"And if we just take this reason or one that Mr. Doub was talking about, you'll see why he said that.","start":3559.404,"stop":3565.611,"duration":6.21},{"text":"These -- these ideas and decision that he's talking about are interlocutory orders and in this case that the Woolsey, it is quite true, there was an interlocutory order that some claimants might come in and file a claim against any proceeds which remained in the hands in the Court.","start":3565.611,"stop":3584.527,"duration":18.92},{"text":"But the fact of the matter is that there were no proceeds in the hands of the Court because the Steel Inventor was declared innocent, there was no fault there.","start":3584.527,"stop":3593.532,"duration":9.01},{"text":"Therefore, in its proceeding the -- there was no fund to distribute.","start":3593.532,"stop":3599.349,"duration":5.82},{"text":"The United States Destroyer, Woolsey, was at the bottom of the Pacific Ocean and since it did not carry freight, the fund that could have been distributed on account of the Woolsey was zero.","start":3599.349,"stop":3610.975,"duration":11.63},{"text":"And therefore, although, United States was found at fault and although people could have claimed, if there had been anything to claim, nobody did.","start":3610.975,"stop":3620.686,"duration":9.71},{"text":"Now, the same thing is true of these other cases.","start":3620.686,"stop":3623.762,"duration":3.08},{"text":"Now, one other matter to straighten up, which at least confused me and the responses to some questions asked by Mr. Justice Brennan.","start":3623.762,"stop":3632.442,"duration":8.68},{"text":"I got the idea that the response was made that if the British Transport Commission had not come to the United States, but it remained in England when this indication proceeding was started, the results of the Courts decision would have been res judicata against it.","start":3632.442,"stop":3651.088,"duration":18.65},{"text":"Now, that of course cannot be settled, the -- no one can be bound by the judgment of the Court, it was not in Court in present.","start":3651.088,"stop":3660.861,"duration":9.77},{"text":"And if this, Your Honors, raises the whole basis of -- of this argument that the purpose of limitation procedures is to bring in to court everybody who has a claim against a limited fund.","start":3660.861,"stop":3676.228,"duration":15.37},{"text":"Now, so far as the American citizens are concerned, our courts can enjoin them.","start":3676.228,"stop":3682.722,"duration":6.49},{"text":"They can say, “You must come in here or be defaulted, and you cannot go into any other court.”","start":3682.722,"stop":3689.081,"duration":6.36},{"text":"But our courts can't control people who are not in the United States, you can't default somebody who isn't in your court.","start":3689.081,"stop":3696.292,"duration":7.21},{"text":"You can't enjoin somebody who is in England.","start":3696.292,"stop":3699.659,"duration":3.37},{"text":"And therefore, these foreign claimants, after they induced to come into these proceedings, and it's highly important that the proceedings should be of such a nature that they will come in.","start":3699.659,"stop":3712.59,"duration":12.93},{"text":"Now, in considering whether to come in, if a claimant is going to find himself, defending himself against all other claimants in the suit he will say, “No, I think I'll just wait.”","start":3712.59,"stop":3723.809,"duration":11.22},{"text":"But as there will be another ship that will come to England before long and I will file a suit against that ship and attach it again a fund in Court, and then -- and have another proceeding in England.","start":3723.809,"stop":3736.645,"duration":12.84},{"text":"And therefore, the whole purpose of the limitation of liability statutes would be defeated that you would not have succeeded in bringing into one proceeding all the claims against one shipowner.","start":3736.645,"stop":3749.368,"duration":12.72},{"text":"And that's why it is so important to do one thing at a time and not try to solve all the issues which possibly could arise.","start":3749.368,"stop":3758.448,"duration":9.08}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Acheson, may I ask this question please.","start":3758.448,"stop":3761.403,"duration":2.95},{"text":"Would it make any difference in your position if both of these ships were American ships?","start":3761.403,"stop":3767.835,"duration":6.43}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"It wouldn't -- it wouldn't make any difference in the argument on this narrow situation.","start":3767.835,"stop":3772.523,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But this is what I mean --","start":3772.523,"stop":3773.537,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"The difference would be, Your Honor, that if both ships were American ships or if the British were present in the United States, then an independent suit could be filed against that shipowner.","start":3773.537,"stop":3787.285,"duration":13.75},{"text":"Once that libel had been filed, the court had taken jurisdiction, the proceedings could be transferred to the same court and consolidate that the whole question here is can you get hold of the person who is sought to be impleaded?","start":3787.285,"stop":3804.002,"duration":16.72},{"text":"And we say that if that person is in the United States, two American ship companies in New York, one starts a limitation proceeding.","start":3804.002,"stop":3816.419,"duration":12.42},{"text":"If the other one is at fault, he will start an independent suit against the other one and then consolidate the proceedings.","start":3816.419,"stop":3823.515,"duration":7.1},{"text":"But you cannot serve them merely because he is in the limitation proceeding.","start":3823.515,"stop":3829.592,"duration":6.08},{"text":"Now, this becomes important in regard to foreigners, because they are not in the United States except as they come in for the limited purpose of the limited liability proceeding.","start":3829.592,"stop":3839.797,"duration":10.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I understand you to say that --","start":3839.797,"stop":3841.414,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":3841.414,"stop":3843.741,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I understand that while they could sue him, bring a separate suit, go to that trouble and then somebody move, and it's moved and have it consolidate it, they couldn't do it directly?","start":3843.741,"stop":3855.508,"duration":11.77}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Have it consolidate or have it not consolidate?","start":3855.508,"stop":3857.966,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, does it mean that although they can do it by the secured dismiss and to file a different suit, they cannot do it unless in the main suit itself expose of all limit?","start":3857.966,"stop":3869.698,"duration":11.73}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"It does not mean that so far as the foreign shipowner is concerned, Mr. Justice Black.","start":3869.698,"stop":3873.699,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm talking about permit to Americans.","start":3873.699,"stop":3875.368,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"So far as an American shipowner is concerned, yes.","start":3875.368,"stop":3878.894,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You've got to go -- that circuit before he can get in to the --","start":3878.894,"stop":3882.64,"duration":3.75}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you have acquired jurisdiction by the service of process.","start":3882.64,"stop":3887.752,"duration":5.11},{"text":"Now, having acquired jurisdiction, you can do in that proceeding what you do in any proceeding, transferred, or consolidated, or not.","start":3887.752,"stop":3895.434,"duration":7.68},{"text":"If you cannot acquire jurisdiction, you cannot do it by serving his lawyer in the limitation proceeding.","start":3895.434,"stop":3903.917,"duration":8.48},{"text":"One other thing that I would like to mention, I -- I misstated the result of the decision in the Moore-McCormack case.","start":3903.917,"stop":3912.736,"duration":8.82},{"text":"I said to the Court that was a proceeding in which a co-claimant had allowed -- allowed to implead in an interlocutory way another co-claimant.","start":3912.736,"stop":3923.381,"duration":10.64},{"text":"That is not correct.","start":3923.381,"stop":3924.378,"duration":1},{"text":"I was in error there.","start":3924.378,"stop":3926.195,"duration":1.82},{"text":"It is a case where a cross-libel was filed.","start":3926.195,"stop":3930.531,"duration":4.34},{"text":"Therefore, that case is like the one which is pending in the District Court and not like the case which is now before Your Honor.","start":3930.531,"stop":3938.851,"duration":8.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Acheson, before you sit down, now that your client is here and came in to this proceeding, if these cross-claims were sustained, is the British Commission in any way prejudiced in the associate of any defenses inclusive for those arising under the ticket contracts or otherwise?","start":3938.851,"stop":3959.124,"duration":20.27}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, it's prejudiced.","start":3959.124,"stop":3961.751,"duration":2.63},{"text":"First of all, in that if -- if it has any limitation of liability rights, they are those under the American statute and not under the British statute.","start":3961.751,"stop":3972.452,"duration":10.7},{"text":"Secondly, all its defenses, the ticket and other defenses or would not be available to win under the Harter Act.","start":3972.452,"stop":3980.109,"duration":7.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Would not be?","start":3980.109,"stop":3981.139,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Would not be, yes, sir.","start":3981.139,"stop":3982.814,"duration":1.67},{"text":"That's why Mr. Dow is very careful to tell you that he does not agree that those -- that American law would not be imposed.","start":3982.814,"stop":3992.788,"duration":9.97},{"text":"American law wouldn't be opposed and that's of course why they wish to sue here.","start":3992.788,"stop":3997.509,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's then to say that in an action in England between you required in any of these cross-claimants, you might hope for a more favorable result and you can under American law?","start":3997.509,"stop":4008.698,"duration":11.19}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That is quite right.","start":4008.698,"stop":4010.211,"duration":1.51},{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":4010.211,"stop":4010.947,"duration":0.74},{"text":"The English law is drawn among in favor of the shipowner than the American law.","start":4010.947,"stop":4017.691,"duration":6.74},{"text":"And therefore, that's their business.","start":4017.691,"stop":4019.156,"duration":1.47},{"text":"It's conducted under that law.","start":4019.156,"stop":4020.268,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean they couldn't set that up at the -- defense in their own courts than how much they would pay (Voice Overlap) --","start":4020.268,"stop":4026.205,"duration":5.94}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"They setup their --","start":4026.205,"stop":4027.218,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- argument that they could.","start":4027.218,"stop":4027.925,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"They setup their contracts as defenses, Mr. Justice Black.","start":4027.925,"stop":4031.902,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose the judgment has been obtained over here fixing the amount and goes to England.","start":4031.902,"stop":4039.852,"duration":7.95},{"text":"Do you mean that they would not have power in their courts to say that while that -- this is the amount would have been due or under their judgment, we can fix this amount?","start":4039.852,"stop":4049.059,"duration":9.21}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I -- I mean that -- in the first place, Mr. Justice Black, those judgments would not be res judicata.","start":4049.059,"stop":4055.493,"duration":6.43},{"text":"And therefore, the whole matter would be tried de novo.","start":4055.493,"stop":4058.993,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then they -- they would have arrived under their law still to setup their limitations?","start":4058.993,"stop":4066.008,"duration":7.01}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is true, sir.","start":4066.008,"stop":4067.159,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And the contract to a right?","start":4067.159,"stop":4068.742,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is true.","start":4068.742,"stop":4078.507,"duration":9.76}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 29, 1957 (Part 1)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13312","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 247, The British Transport Commission, Petitioner, versus United States of America, as Owner of The U.S.N.S. Haiti Victory, et al.","start":0,"stop":17.899,"duration":17.9},{"text":"Mr. Acheson.","start":17.899,"stop":25.029,"duration":7.13}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":25.029,"stop":27.452,"duration":2.42},{"text":"This is an admiralty case.","start":27.452,"stop":30.442,"duration":2.99},{"text":"It -- it comes before the Court on a limited writ of certiorari for the Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit and the limitation of the writ restricts the argument today to a question of admiralty procedure, but the case is not the less important, I hope, because of that.","start":30.442,"stop":50.411,"duration":19.97},{"text":"I think there is eminent authority for the view that legal progress is secreted in the intestacies of legal procedure and it is there that we have to look for it in this case.","start":50.411,"stop":62.695,"duration":12.28},{"text":"The question of procedure, which comes before the Court is a simple one.","start":62.695,"stop":67.308,"duration":4.61},{"text":"It is whether “claimants” in a limitation of liability proceeding may undertake to subject one of their number to liability by proceeding against him under Rule 56 of the Admiralty Rules and this, of course, requires a consideration of the statutes involved and of the Admiralty Rules which are applicable.","start":67.308,"stop":92.466,"duration":25.16},{"text":"Now, briefly, the case comes before the Court in this posture.","start":92.466,"stop":96.43,"duration":3.96},{"text":"The United States as the owner of the Naval Transport, Haiti Victory, which had run in to the British Transport Commission across channel ferry in European waters, ordered its ship to return to the United States.","start":96.43,"stop":111.81,"duration":15.38},{"text":"It did so return.","start":111.81,"stop":112.967,"duration":1.16},{"text":"It entered the port of Norfolk and the United States there brought limitation of liability proceedings to restrict its liability and also to ask for exoneration.","start":112.967,"stop":126.518,"duration":13.55},{"text":"A monition order issued in accordance with the practice and 115 claimants appeared in the Norfolk proceeding.","start":126.518,"stop":134.948,"duration":8.43},{"text":"Of these 115 claimants, 104 were residents of England and the continent.","start":134.948,"stop":143.971,"duration":9.02},{"text":"The American claimants, the 11 American claimants who entered the proceeding, the total amount of their claims was less than one-half of the value of the Haiti Victory and in sufficient sum to support by itself a limitation of liability proceeding.","start":143.971,"stop":162.455,"duration":18.48},{"text":"During before the file, during the course of the proceedings, the sum of the claimants undertook to implead under Rule 56, the British Transport Commission one of the claimants in the proceeding and sought to allege that the British Transport Commission was liable for the accident, and therefore, it should respond in damages.","start":162.455,"stop":182.511,"duration":20.06},{"text":"The District Court rejected this attempt and said that a limitation proceeding did not provide a forum in which claimants might adjust their liabilities to one another.","start":182.511,"stop":196.248,"duration":13.74},{"text":"The United States, in answer to the claim filed by the British Transport Commission, set up a settle alleging that this was under the divided liability law where both ships might be held at fault, so that its damages, which were comparatively small, might be off set against the one-half of the damages which it might be called on to pay, which have incurred to the Haiti Victory.","start":196.248,"stop":225.167,"duration":28.92},{"text":"A trial was held, and at the trial, the Haiti Victory was exonerated from liability and the District Court found that the Duke of York, the British Transport Commission vessel was solely at fault.","start":225.167,"stop":237.46,"duration":12.29},{"text":"All parties appealed to the Court of Appeals.","start":237.46,"stop":241.027,"duration":3.57},{"text":"In the Court of Appeals, the question of fault was affirmed, and this Court has refused to review that finding.","start":241.027,"stop":249.498,"duration":8.47},{"text":"However, on the procedural question, the Court of Appeals reversed the District Court, saying that the precise issue on which it reversed the District Court was whether one claimant in a limitation of liability proceeding could implead, could sue another claimant in that proceeding.","start":249.498,"stop":273.327,"duration":23.83},{"text":"After the decision of the Court of Appeals, the record was remanded to the District Court.","start":273.327,"stop":278.568,"duration":5.24},{"text":"And there, the United States filed what it calls a cross-claim against the British Transport Commission, a claim seeking to set up affirmative liability to the United States on the part of the British Transport Commission.","start":278.568,"stop":293.534,"duration":14.97},{"text":"That matter, a rule of motion to dismiss, has been entered and that is now pending in the District Court.","start":293.534,"stop":300.016,"duration":6.48},{"text":"It is not before this Court.","start":300.016,"stop":302.018,"duration":2},{"text":"It is not a part of this appeal.","start":302.018,"stop":304.68,"duration":2.66},{"text":"Though, from the brief of the Government, there seems to be every probability that it will be argued.","start":304.68,"stop":311.727,"duration":7.05},{"text":"The question then comes down to consider Rule 56.","start":311.727,"stop":317.327,"duration":5.6},{"text":"Does Rule 56, by its terms, in the light of its history, in the light of its analysis, does that describe a limitation of liability proceeding?","start":317.327,"stop":327.683,"duration":10.36},{"text":"Does it describe as those who can take advantage of Rule 56, co-claimants in the limitation of liability proceeding?","start":327.683,"stop":337.778,"duration":10.1},{"text":"Or to put it in a broader way, which the United States seems to put it, are the rules of procedure in admiralty so amorphous, so vague, that a proceeding started to litigate the liability of the United States and to limit that liability if -- if it was found to exist can be turned in to a suit by other parties against another person?","start":337.778,"stop":364.516,"duration":26.74},{"text":"You know admiralty practice, the rule of limitation, statute having to do with the limitation of liability as some 30 years older than the third party practice of Rule 56.","start":364.516,"stop":378.799,"duration":14.28},{"text":"So, we will consider with your Court's permission, limitation of liability first.","start":378.799,"stop":386.004,"duration":7.21},{"text":"This is a legislative graft upon principles of admiralty.","start":386.004,"stop":391.343,"duration":5.34},{"text":"We hear about limitation of liability first in the French ordinance of 1681.","start":391.343,"stop":397.255,"duration":5.91},{"text":"Half a century later, it crosses the channel and that appears in the statute of seven -- George II.","start":397.255,"stop":404.016,"duration":6.76},{"text":"Then, a hundred years went by before it crossed the Atlantic Ocean.","start":404.016,"stop":407.924,"duration":3.91},{"text":"Then, the Steam of Lexington burned at sea with a cargo of gold and as a result of that disaster, Congress in 1851, enacted the limitation of liability statute, which said that the lost of a shipowner on a count of a disaster occurring among other things by collision might be limited if he will not prevail and had no knowledge of the cost of this disaster.","start":407.924,"stop":433.311,"duration":25.39},{"text":"It might be limited to the value of a ship, plus the value of the freight, which was then pending.","start":433.311,"stop":441.816,"duration":8.5},{"text":"The idea, the historic idea of this practice is to limit the risk of the shipowner to what is called the fortunes de mer, the amount which is risk on the voyage shall be the value of the ship and should be separated with the fortune de terre, which is the general assets of the shipowner.","start":441.816,"stop":462.21,"duration":20.39},{"text":"This defense could be setup obviously, when one is proceeded against.","start":462.21,"stop":467.838,"duration":5.63},{"text":"That's the normal way to do it, but the statute contemplated that there might be affirmative proceedings by which the injured, the shipowner who -- whose liability was at stake might take initial action to raise the issue.","start":467.838,"stop":482.761,"duration":14.92},{"text":"And the rules were laid down to that.","start":482.761,"stop":484.717,"duration":1.96},{"text":"It was left entirely to this Court to announce the rules.","start":484.717,"stop":489.762,"duration":5.05},{"text":"And 20 years went by before this Court did that.","start":489.762,"stop":493.914,"duration":4.15},{"text":"Finally, Mr. Justice Bradley, in the case of Norwich Transportation Company versus Wright, announced that the Court had given a thought to a rather confused practice which had grown out and that -- on that day, it was announcing the Admiralty Rules which became the procedural guides for limitation of liability proceedings.","start":493.914,"stop":515.629,"duration":21.72},{"text":"Now, these rules are quite simple and they say that the proceeding is initiated by a petition.","start":515.629,"stop":522.644,"duration":7.01},{"text":"The shipowner may file that petition in any district where the ship may be.","start":522.644,"stop":529.321,"duration":6.68},{"text":"If the ship is not in any district, he may file it wherever he is sued.","start":529.321,"stop":533.887,"duration":4.57},{"text":"If he isn't sued and if the ship isn't in any district, he may file it wherever he wishes in the United States.","start":533.887,"stop":540.767,"duration":6.88},{"text":"The petition prays for exoneration from liability for the exit.","start":540.767,"stop":545.989,"duration":5.22},{"text":"Or if that be denied for the limitation of liability to the value of the ship and her freights, the petition must setout the value of the ship and her freights, and when the petitioner is someone other than the sovereign, he must file security which forms a fund in the hands of the Court to be divided among the claimants.","start":545.989,"stop":571.259,"duration":25.27},{"text":"The rules provide that a monition shall issue and be published in courts, which are directed by the Court issuing.","start":571.259,"stop":580.045,"duration":8.79},{"text":"In this case, it was published in the Courts of England, the monition of the petition, I suppose to state the parties who have been injured so far as they are known.","start":580.045,"stop":591.08,"duration":11.04},{"text":"And in this case, some 17 people who were mentioned by the United States in its petition as having been killed or injured of whom 13 were residents of England and Europe.","start":591.08,"stop":603.535,"duration":12.45},{"text":"And as part of the procedure, also, an injunction is issued by the Court where the petitioner has been filed enjoining all claimants from proceeding in any other court except that one.","start":603.535,"stop":615.909,"duration":12.37},{"text":"Then, there is a trial on the merits.","start":615.909,"stop":618.454,"duration":2.54},{"text":"And as a result of that trial, the first decision has to do with the question of fault.","start":618.454,"stop":623.798,"duration":5.34},{"text":"If the shipowner is found not to admit its fault, then his security is returned to him and the matter is finished.","start":623.798,"stop":630.825,"duration":7.03},{"text":"If however, it is claimed that it's found that he is at fault, then, the fund in the hands of the Court distributed among the claimants.","start":630.825,"stop":640.142,"duration":9.32},{"text":"Now, Your Honors can see that this is not like an ordinary judicial proceeding.","start":640.142,"stop":645.214,"duration":5.07},{"text":"It's one that starts backwards.","start":645.214,"stop":646.934,"duration":1.72},{"text":"It's one which is started by a person who imagines himself to be a defendant.","start":646.934,"stop":652.166,"duration":5.23},{"text":"He initiates the litigation by filing this petition.","start":652.166,"stop":656.626,"duration":4.46},{"text":"And so, Judge Benedict, the leading writer on this subject, describes it as a special proceeding sui generis and indeed, it is.","start":656.626,"stop":665.082,"duration":8.46},{"text":"His purpose was to raise the question of the liability of the shipowner, to bring into that Court all claimants against the ship, to restrict the liability to the value of the ship if he was liable at all, and -- and to distribute the assets.","start":665.082,"stop":681.248,"duration":16.17},{"text":"And in further -- furtherance of that purpose, for over a century, this Court has given a broad and equitable construction to the Act.","start":681.248,"stop":693.649,"duration":12.4},{"text":"It has described it as a useful but drastic measure, a measure which in the language of Chief Justice Taft brings in against their will all the claimants and prevents them from establishing their claims in any other court.","start":693.649,"stop":708.363,"duration":14.71},{"text":"It's a very drastic proceeding, but it's a useful one and for its purposes, it has been generously construed.","start":708.363,"stop":717.43,"duration":9.07},{"text":"But in all the years of the existence of this statute, 106 years, the last third of March, not $1 has ever been recovered by anybody in any Court of the United States against a claimant in the limitation proceeding, not $1.","start":717.43,"stop":737.212,"duration":19.78},{"text":"We will have the occasion later on to examine in it into that and I believe that you'll find that that is the case.","start":737.212,"stop":745.521,"duration":8.31}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that, Mr. Acheson, because the courts didn't accept jurisdiction in that sense?","start":745.521,"stop":752.463,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's because in most of the cases, they held that they could not sue.","start":752.463,"stop":756.458,"duration":4},{"text":"But in those where they did permit someone to be brought in, they found that the liability was otherwise.","start":756.458,"stop":763.566,"duration":7.11},{"text":"So that what I am saying rather, startling way in -- in part to startle my learned friend on my right here is that in all the history of the United States, no one has ever succeeded in recovering a dollar in this proceeding.","start":763.566,"stop":780.791,"duration":17.23},{"text":"Now, if we turn from limitation of liability to Rule 56, you'll see that this is a wholly different kind of a proceeding.","start":780.791,"stop":789.046,"duration":8.25},{"text":"Rule 56 was thought by the other respondents in this suit and by the two lower courts to be the source of authority if there was any authority for any proceeding against the British Maritime Commission.","start":789.046,"stop":804.192,"duration":15.15},{"text":"It turned on the construction of that rule, the United States thinks not.","start":804.192,"stop":807.765,"duration":3.57},{"text":"The United States thinks this could be done regardless of the rule, but both the lower courts and the other respondents believe the rule to be detached though.","start":807.765,"stop":818.179,"duration":10.41},{"text":"Now, Rule 56 came about as a result of decision of Judge Addison Brown in 1883 in the case of the Hudson, and Judge Brown's decision has came about by reason of a decision of this Court in the Atlas in 1876.","start":818.179,"stop":837.806,"duration":19.63},{"text":"Now, what this Court decided in the Atlas was that contrary to the law of England, that if a person was libeled, if the shipowner was libeled and found at fault, even though it was found only partly at fault, the libelants could recover from that shipowner the full amount of the damages, and the shipowner was then left to pursue contribution from his joint tortfeasor or feasors.","start":837.806,"stop":865.789,"duration":27.98},{"text":"That became the law of United States because Your Honors said it was and it is different from the law England.","start":865.789,"stop":871.635,"duration":5.85},{"text":"As a result of that, Judge Brown said, “Very well, if this is the law, therefore, if a defendant if in a libel proceeding, the shipowner who is defended, if he claims that another ship was equally at fault,” Judge Brown said, “I will issue an auxiliary writ and bring him in as a defendant into this proceeding, so that he may share the burden of the defense and pay the damages if damages there be.”","start":871.635,"stop":899.276,"duration":27.64},{"text":"And that's was Rule 56 is.","start":899.276,"stop":901.919,"duration":2.64},{"text":"And as it was originally enacted, it was a rule solely having to do with collision cases later on.It came to other -- other cases of injury too, but the original rule is very simple although the language bears out Mr. Justice Frankfurter's description a moment ago in some statutes which are not wholly illiterate.","start":901.919,"stop":925.307,"duration":23.39},{"text":"On page 15, the statute reads as follows.","start":925.307,"stop":930.495,"duration":5.19},{"text":"“In a suit for damage by collision,” now later on, it was extended beyond that.","start":930.495,"stop":935.181,"duration":4.69},{"text":"“If the claimant of any vessel proceeded against or any respondent proceeded against in personam shall, by petition, are now presented before at the time of answering the libel or within such further time as the Court may allow and containing a suitable allegation shall enfold on negligence in any other vessel contributing to the same collision and the particulars thereof, and that such other vessel or any other party ought to be proceeded against in the same suit for such damage.”","start":935.181,"stop":965.633,"duration":30.45},{"text":"Now, we go back to the word.","start":965.633,"stop":967.227,"duration":1.59},{"text":"“If the claimant show -- shall, in a play, that process be issued against such vessel or party to that end, such process may be issued.”","start":967.227,"stop":979.593,"duration":12.37},{"text":"Now, what that meant is what I said a moment ago, that if a defendant, somebody who is proceeded against, believes that somebody else ought to be proceeded against as well, he may issue, of course, to have issue an auxiliary writ to bring in that other shipowner as a defendant.","start":979.593,"stop":998.746,"duration":19.15},{"text":"Now, Your Honors will see that this rule is talking and applicable to libel proceedings.","start":998.746,"stop":1005.067,"duration":6.32},{"text":"It talks all the way through the rule of the libel.","start":1005.067,"stop":1008.687,"duration":3.62},{"text":"It says, “At the time when the rule is to be invoked, is before or at the time of answering the libel.","start":1008.687,"stop":1015.918,"duration":7.23},{"text":"It's invoked by a defendant who is caused on the Court upon to answer something.","start":1015.918,"stop":1022.338,"duration":6.42},{"text":"After service, there must be personal service upon the third party to be brought in.","start":1022.338,"stop":1027.417,"duration":5.08},{"text":"After service, such suit shall proceed as if such vessel or person had been originally proceeded against.","start":1027.417,"stop":1035.462,"duration":8.05},{"text":"Now, that's a libel action.","start":1035.462,"stop":1036.661,"duration":1.2},{"text":"That's where you originally proceed against them.","start":1036.661,"stop":1040.309,"duration":3.65},{"text":"And when brought in, this third party shall do what?","start":1040.309,"stop":1044.109,"duration":3.8},{"text":"The first thing he shall do is to answer the libel.","start":1044.109,"stop":1048.086,"duration":3.98},{"text":"Rule 56 is a rule which is applicable to libel proceedings and it's made so by its language and it's also made so by the inherent nature of the two proceedings.","start":1048.086,"stop":1062.315,"duration":14.23},{"text":"It is wholly irrelevant to a limitation of liability proceedings what rights claimants may have in to say.","start":1062.315,"stop":1070.738,"duration":8.42},{"text":"The whole question of the -- of the shipowners, the petitioning shipowner's liability can be settled.","start":1070.738,"stop":1076.616,"duration":5.88},{"text":"The whole fund in the hands of the Court can be distributed without being destructed in any way by the claims of claimants against one another.","start":1076.616,"stop":1085.265,"duration":8.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"If the libelant conceived that he's had a claim against the third party, did it assert that claim once the third party has been brought in?","start":1085.265,"stop":1094.139,"duration":8.87}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if the United States had a claim against the British Transport Commission, it can sue the British Transport Commission wherever it can sue the British Transport Commission.","start":1094.139,"stop":1105.988,"duration":11.85},{"text":"But the whole point of my argument is that coming in as a claimant does not subject oneself to the jurisdiction of the Court for purpose of service as a -- of a cross-libel.","start":1105.988,"stop":1118.936,"duration":12.95},{"text":"Now, the United States as cross-libel is not before Your Honors at this time.","start":1118.936,"stop":1122.781,"duration":3.85},{"text":"That is pending in the District Court.","start":1122.781,"stop":1124.928,"duration":2.15},{"text":"What is before Your Honors is an attempt by other claimants to make a defendant out of the British Transport Commission.","start":1124.928,"stop":1134.951,"duration":10.02},{"text":"But to answer your question, Mr. Justice Harlan, coming in as a claimant does not give that personal appearance in the jurisdiction which will warrant service upon the practice of a cross-libel.","start":1134.951,"stop":1149.811,"duration":14.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Would the -- would the Court have had any jurisdiction at all against the Commission in a direct suit against it?","start":1149.811,"stop":1157.822,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1157.822,"stop":1158.256,"duration":0.43},{"text":"The Court would not have any jurisdiction because the Commission is a British Corporation in England and can of course be sued in England.","start":1158.256,"stop":1167.46,"duration":9.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Supposed the Commission had not come into the limitation proceedings, what would be its position on the basis of its attitude, namely, that the United States Transport was to blame?","start":1167.46,"stop":1178.963,"duration":11.5}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, its position, Your Honor, would have to be on that.","start":1178.963,"stop":1182.177,"duration":3.21},{"text":"It would have had to sue the United States either in libel in the United States or wait until the Haiti Victory or some other ship owned by the United States went into a British harbor and then attach it and sue it in England.","start":1182.177,"stop":1194.837,"duration":12.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It would not be bound by the limitation of --","start":1194.837,"stop":1196.613,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Not at all.","start":1196.613,"stop":1196.785,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- proceedings of which it was not a party?","start":1196.785,"stop":1198.469,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Not at all, sir, not at all.","start":1198.469,"stop":1200.601,"duration":2.13},{"text":"If it were an American Corporation, resident in the United States, Your Honor, it would be bound by the injunction so that it could not sue in any other Court.","start":1200.601,"stop":1210.697,"duration":10.1},{"text":"But if it were in England and not present and not subject to the injunction of the Norfolk Court, then of course it could proceed where it wish to proceed it and could get service.","start":1210.697,"stop":1219.496,"duration":8.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"To talk about this being an in rem adjudication is loose talk.","start":1219.496,"stop":1223.758,"duration":4.26},{"text":"I mean it's in rem as to limitation.","start":1223.758,"stop":1225.957,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is correct.","start":1225.957,"stop":1226.927,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But not as to claims that you may have against the owner of the ship to which you couldn't be jurisdictionally be compelled to be a party?","start":1226.927,"stop":1234.79,"duration":7.86}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That is quite correct, Your Honor.","start":1234.79,"stop":1235.967,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"If it does terminate the limitation of it, what is the difference as to the issues that can -- that ought to be tried and the evidences to be introduced, that kind of proceeding in one word is a direct libel against the ship?","start":1235.967,"stop":1251.921,"duration":15.95}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if the British Corporation came into the United States and filed a direct libel, then, it would be subject to a cross-libel, no question about that.","start":1251.921,"stop":1262.32,"duration":10.4}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What I meant was this.","start":1262.32,"stop":1263.406,"duration":1.09},{"text":"There are certain issues that have to be tried out in this limitation proceeding where the British Company comes as British associates, whatever it is, comes in and files its claim.","start":1263.406,"stop":1275.837,"duration":12.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What are the differences in the issues that have to be tried in that proceeding and the issues that have to be tried out if he -- if it were to sue the company directly?","start":1275.837,"stop":1285.061,"duration":9.22}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"They are different in this respect, in this respect only, Mr. Justice Black.","start":1285.061,"stop":1289.14,"duration":4.08},{"text":"The question of fault is before the Court in the limitation proceeding as it would be in a libel proceeding and that issue is fully decided, have now result of the decision as res judicata, that everyone is bound by the finding.","start":1289.14,"stop":1305.55,"duration":16.41}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That --","start":1305.55,"stop":1305.671,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Now --","start":1305.671,"stop":1305.999,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- same effect would occur -- the suit was between and directed not in the limitation.","start":1305.999,"stop":1309.836,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That is quite correct, Your Honor.","start":1309.836,"stop":1311.354,"duration":1.52},{"text":"It would.","start":1311.354,"stop":1311.991,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what is the difference?","start":1311.991,"stop":1312.776,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, the other -- the difference is that if this were a libel and cross-libel, then claims against the Haiti Victory could come before the Court, had to be decided.","start":1312.776,"stop":1323.786,"duration":11.01},{"text":"But those claims cannot come before the Court in a limitation proceeding which was restricted solely to the question of the liability and the limitation of a liability of the petition.","start":1323.786,"stop":1334.803,"duration":11.02}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, wouldn't that -- would they do not determine the liability of the United States ship at all in that?","start":1334.803,"stop":1341.628,"duration":6.82}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, they -- the -- in the limitation proceeding, they determined the question of fault, everybody's fault that is determined.","start":1341.628,"stop":1351.681,"duration":10.05},{"text":"Furthermore, so far as the United States is concern, if it is found not at fault, then there is no further proceeding --","start":1351.681,"stop":1359.013,"duration":7.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"If it found at fault?","start":1359.013,"stop":1360.292,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Then, the fund, the value of the ship plus the freight, if there were any freight would be divided among the claimants.","start":1360.292,"stop":1366.336,"duration":6.04}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The difference is -- is there any more difference than the fact that a Government would get out for less because it has limitation proceedings, that it would -- there were direct suits without limitation?","start":1366.336,"stop":1376.179,"duration":9.84}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"The difference is whose liability is being adjudicated.","start":1376.179,"stop":1379.972,"duration":3.79},{"text":"And in the limitation proceeding, the -- that liability is being adjudicated which is petitioned to be adjudicated, i.e., in that of the United States.","start":1379.972,"stop":1390.779,"duration":10.81},{"text":"In the libel and cross-libel then the liability of both parties that is the damages which they pay is adjudicated.","start":1390.779,"stop":1399.215,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would it have made any difference -- would it make any difference if the British Commission had formally just like a appearing especially could have appeared especially in terms?","start":1399.215,"stop":1411.593,"duration":12.38},{"text":"I understand your argument is that it doesn't have to do that, but if in terms as I've said, we come into a Court into which we couldn't be dragged because the Atlantic Ocean separates us from service.","start":1411.593,"stop":1423.946,"duration":12.35},{"text":"We appear in this Court restrictively for purposes of the limitation where in your view that makes it -- have made any difference?","start":1423.946,"stop":1432.739,"duration":8.79}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we -- we believe that is why --","start":1432.739,"stop":1435.605,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":1435.605,"stop":1435.903,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe putting it in words has any particularly sectors of that.","start":1435.903,"stop":1439.372,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if -- what you say if -- if they -- if they're not so limited as a matter of law by the nature of the proceeding, they couldn't limit themselves by a piece of paper.","start":1439.372,"stop":1451.313,"duration":11.94}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That's quite right Your Honor.","start":1451.313,"stop":1452.533,"duration":1.22},{"text":"The --","start":1452.533,"stop":1452.618,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose.","start":1452.618,"stop":1453.365,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"The form of incantation would not have the --","start":1453.365,"stop":1454.719,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1454.719,"stop":1454.936,"duration":0.22},{"text":"This is -- this would not be a special appearance challenging the jurisdiction.","start":1454.936,"stop":1459.323,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":1459.323,"stop":1460.033,"duration":0.71},{"text":"They -- they are -- clearly, they are tearing for the sole thing which the statute and rules says is involved in the proceeding.","start":1460.033,"stop":1467.695,"duration":7.66},{"text":"That is, is the United States liable at all?","start":1467.695,"stop":1471.32,"duration":3.63},{"text":"And if so, who gets what share of the fund in the hands of the Court?","start":1471.32,"stop":1475.584,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Acheson, did you say that there had been a finding affirmatively that the Duke of York was at fault in this --","start":1475.584,"stop":1483.031,"duration":7.45}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That was found by the trial court and affirmed by the Court of Appeals.","start":1483.031,"stop":1487.294,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, would that issue be open that your contention today is correct in a proceeding by one of the co-claimants in England, let's say, where the Duke of York was found?","start":1487.294,"stop":1499.412,"duration":12.12}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Mr. Justice Brennan.","start":1499.412,"stop":1500.488,"duration":1.08},{"text":"That is res adjudicata.","start":1500.488,"stop":1501.914,"duration":1.43},{"text":"That -- that issue is closed.","start":1501.914,"stop":1503.205,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Anywhere?","start":1503.205,"stop":1503.881,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Anywhere, anytime at any court.","start":1503.881,"stop":1506.603,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In the manners between the -- among the co-claimants?","start":1506.603,"stop":1509.198,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Among all parties who appeared in that proceeding.","start":1509.198,"stop":1512.277,"duration":3.08},{"text":"They are bound by the judgement of the two lower courts, which this Court would now review, but the United States was not at fault, the Duke or York was at fault.","start":1512.277,"stop":1521.817,"duration":9.54},{"text":"That is said.","start":1521.817,"stop":1523.255,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What would be left for the claimant and the new ship?","start":1523.255,"stop":1525.95,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"It's proceeding to prove their claims, get a judgement for their claims.","start":1525.95,"stop":1531.579,"duration":5.63}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the total -- that's all that would be there?","start":1531.579,"stop":1533.646,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That's all that is left, yes, Mr. Justice Black.","start":1533.646,"stop":1537.105,"duration":3.46},{"text":"And let me speak for a moment about that.","start":1537.105,"stop":1538.918,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, excuse me a minute.","start":1538.918,"stop":1540.146,"duration":1.23},{"text":"May I ask you some further question if I may please?","start":1540.146,"stop":1543.022,"duration":2.88},{"text":"If that's all that would be left just the judgement for the amount of their claims, in what proceeding will the Duke of York be able to have a limitation of liability in respect to the aggregate of those claims?","start":1543.022,"stop":1556.131,"duration":13.11}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, that -- that is a very good question, Your Honor.","start":1556.131,"stop":1562.592,"duration":6.46},{"text":"I want to wish I was ready to address myself, because under the Government's claim, I think it looks as though the Duke of York would have no recourse to any limitation.","start":1562.592,"stop":1575.453,"duration":12.86},{"text":"The Government says, “Probably it would, but it doesn't know.”","start":1575.453,"stop":1578.618,"duration":3.16},{"text":"And the reason it doesn't know is that if this trial takes place in the United States, there was an amendment to the limitation of liability statute in 1946.","start":1578.618,"stop":1588.486,"duration":9.87},{"text":"And that amendment said that “A proceeding for limitation must be started within six months of the time when a shipowner is notified of the claim.”","start":1588.486,"stop":1598.89,"duration":10.4},{"text":"Now, you can see it what's about that, what questions that raise.","start":1598.89,"stop":1603.552,"duration":4.66},{"text":"The question it raised is, does this apply to a limitation as a defense or only as an aggressive act?","start":1603.552,"stop":1610.305,"duration":6.75},{"text":"And on that, you will not be surprised to hear that the courts are evenly divided, absolutely evenly on that question.","start":1610.305,"stop":1616.457,"duration":6.15},{"text":"Half of them say, “The six months limitation applies to everything.","start":1616.457,"stop":1621.811,"duration":5.35},{"text":"You cannot plead limitation as a defense.","start":1621.811,"stop":1624.383,"duration":2.57},{"text":"You cannot certify petitioner.”","start":1624.383,"stop":1626.732,"duration":2.35},{"text":"The other half of the courts say, “It does not apply to pleading as a defense.","start":1626.732,"stop":1631.6,"duration":4.87},{"text":"It only applies to taking the affirmative step.”","start":1631.6,"stop":1634.862,"duration":3.26},{"text":"And the only Court of Appeals which has expressed itself on this has said that it applies to both defense and the other.","start":1634.862,"stop":1643.033,"duration":8.17},{"text":"Now, the Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit, in overruling the District Court, I was following out some of the thoughts which are in the minds of Your Honors.","start":1643.033,"stop":1652.355,"duration":9.32},{"text":"And it felt two -- there were two great reasons why this should be done, why should it reverse the District Court.","start":1652.355,"stop":1660.89,"duration":8.54},{"text":"One was because it said, “There would be grave hardships imposed upon the claimants if it did not do so,” and the other was, “because equitable principles required it to do so.”","start":1660.89,"stop":1672.519,"duration":11.63},{"text":"Now, these hardships are three in number as stated by the Court.","start":1672.519,"stop":1677.936,"duration":5.42},{"text":"They are, that if the Court of Norfolk doesn't decide this, there will have to be another proceeding.","start":1677.936,"stop":1684.158,"duration":6.22},{"text":"Second one is this other proceeding will be at great expense.","start":1684.158,"stop":1688.454,"duration":4.3},{"text":"The third one is that it will be at a time when perhaps much of the evidence necessary to support their claims would have been lost.","start":1688.454,"stop":1696.899,"duration":8.44},{"text":"Now, when we examined these, we -- we found it a rather confusing situation.","start":1696.899,"stop":1702.566,"duration":5.67},{"text":"There must be another proceeding in any event.","start":1702.566,"stop":1706,"duration":3.43},{"text":"This is a British Corporation.","start":1706,"stop":1708.149,"duration":2.15},{"text":"Whatever judgements it gets in Norfolk, these judgements are collected in England.","start":1708.149,"stop":1713.608,"duration":5.46},{"text":"And when a claimant goes to England to collect, the first thing that the British Transport Corporation will plead is the British statute of limitation, not at that time, but limitation of liability.","start":1713.608,"stop":1728.557,"duration":14.95},{"text":"Now, the British limitation of liability statute is different from ours.","start":1728.557,"stop":1732.994,"duration":4.44},{"text":"It's more favorable to shipowners than ours.","start":1732.994,"stop":1735.975,"duration":2.98},{"text":"It's one to which this corporation is entitled in an English court and an English court will give it that benefit.","start":1735.975,"stop":1743.418,"duration":7.44},{"text":"So, there is one reason of why they must be --","start":1743.418,"stop":1746.923,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, where would you think these lawsuits occur?","start":1746.923,"stop":1748.727,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon, sir?","start":1748.727,"stop":1749.957,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where would the British company lose anything by having a value of this claim fixed here and then finally, simply say, “We our only liable to the amount of the percentage of the total on our British men limitation act?”","start":1749.957,"stop":1770.127,"duration":20.17}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, it -- it would lose this.","start":1770.127,"stop":1772.835,"duration":2.71},{"text":"In the first place, there are 104 people involved here who are residents of the continent in England -- on England.","start":1772.835,"stop":1782.301,"duration":9.47},{"text":"So far as hardship for them is concerned, there's certainly far or less hardship to litigating where you live than in litigating across the Atlantic.","start":1782.301,"stop":1790.072,"duration":7.77},{"text":"So far as lost of evidence due to time is concerned, they presented much more easily and much more quickly and with less chance of laws in an English court that over here in Norfolk where everybody has to cross the ocean to do it.","start":1790.072,"stop":1804.099,"duration":14.03},{"text":"And furthermore, there's another great loss if they would infer.","start":1804.099,"stop":1808.593,"duration":4.49},{"text":"And that is not only just the British limitation of liabilities statute applied, but under the British law, it has two contract limitations of liability.","start":1808.593,"stop":1818.251,"duration":9.66},{"text":"They do not have the Harter Act provisions in this country.","start":1818.251,"stop":1821.815,"duration":3.56},{"text":"And therefore, when contracts of affreightment are made or when personal passages are arranged, what the degrees of liability and for how much are determined?","start":1821.815,"stop":1832.377,"duration":10.56},{"text":"Those are invalid in an American court.","start":1832.377,"stop":1834.723,"duration":2.35},{"text":"They are not invalid in an English court.","start":1834.723,"stop":1837.727,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean they would have to relitigate to some extent --","start":1837.727,"stop":1841.185,"duration":3.46}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1841.185,"stop":1841.404,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the amount due by reason of that difference in the law?","start":1841.404,"stop":1845.344,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they would have to do it for that reason and for another reason.","start":1845.344,"stop":1848.412,"duration":3.07},{"text":"And the other reason would -- would be that a decision in the Norfolk court as to the liability of the amount of the liability of the British Transport Commission to various claimants would not be res judicata in England.","start":1848.412,"stop":1863.726,"duration":15.31},{"text":"And it would not be res judicata because, the English courts would say and properly say that at the time that the British Transport Commission appeared in the United States, the law was perfectly obvious to anyone who is not perhaps a lawyer.","start":1863.726,"stop":1882.417,"duration":18.69},{"text":"That it was not subjecting itself to the determination of its own liability.","start":1882.417,"stop":1888.055,"duration":5.64},{"text":"It is not doing that at all.","start":1888.055,"stop":1890.613,"duration":2.56},{"text":"The -- the rule was clear.","start":1890.613,"stop":1892.134,"duration":1.52},{"text":"The statute was clear.","start":1892.134,"stop":1893.969,"duration":1.84},{"text":"The unbroken course of decisions of our courts have -- had been in that direction.","start":1893.969,"stop":1899.74,"duration":5.77},{"text":"And as I say, nobody had collected a cent in 106 years.","start":1899.74,"stop":1904.703,"duration":4.96},{"text":"Therefore, the British courts would say, “Our national did not enter the American courts for the purpose of having its liability, if any, to your claimants determined.","start":1904.703,"stop":1916.284,"duration":11.58},{"text":"And whatever the American court did is not res judicata.","start":1916.284,"stop":1919.868,"duration":3.58},{"text":"And we will relitigate that court because we have our own statute of limitation of liability.","start":1919.868,"stop":1927.348,"duration":7.48},{"text":"We have our own contractual reasons for liability, and -- and we're all here in Europe, and I have all our evidence here.","start":1927.348,"stop":1935.571,"duration":8.22},{"text":"And therefore, that would be done.”","start":1935.571,"stop":1939.042,"duration":3.47},{"text":"So, that --","start":1939.042,"stop":1939.435,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't quite understand that.","start":1939.435,"stop":1940.7,"duration":1.27},{"text":"You mean that, if it's the law of this country -- I can understand why they might relitigate any of them, because it says that it couldn't be properly litigated here.","start":1940.7,"stop":1949.686,"duration":8.99}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I meant.","start":1949.686,"stop":1950.106,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean they would say, they would review our decisions to see whether we should have taken it?","start":1950.106,"stop":1955.185,"duration":5.08}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1955.185,"stop":1955.511,"duration":0.33},{"text":"They -- they would say that the decision as to the liability of the British Transport Commission, two individual claimants was not res judicata at all.","start":1955.511,"stop":1966.507,"duration":11},{"text":"It was persuasive.","start":1966.507,"stop":1967.55,"duration":1.04},{"text":"It will be interesting.","start":1967.55,"stop":1968.679,"duration":1.13},{"text":"It could be introduced, and then it might be followed by the Court, but it would not be compelling upon the Court.","start":1968.679,"stop":1975.329,"duration":6.65},{"text":"Now, that may be very clear about one distinction.","start":1975.329,"stop":1978.586,"duration":3.26},{"text":"It is res judicata as to who is at fault.","start":1978.586,"stop":1982.387,"duration":3.8},{"text":"That point would not be relitigated.","start":1982.387,"stop":1985.017,"duration":2.63},{"text":"That was clear, that --","start":1985.017,"stop":1985.977,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understood that.","start":1985.977,"stop":1986.442,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but this Court would -- would accept that, but it would not say, “We have a judgment which is a binding judgment on our case, because the Norfolk --","start":1986.442,"stop":1993.653,"duration":7.21}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I can understand that argument if you -- you're saying that they just want to separate res judicata and the reference to the amount because they have their own laws and their own rules to determine it.","start":1993.653,"stop":2004.058,"duration":10.4}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the English --","start":2004.058,"stop":2004.514,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't quite understand how it would make any difference if they might have thought, we would hold this and didn't have jurisdiction all over again.","start":2004.514,"stop":2011.712,"duration":7.2}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"The English law, Your Honor, on res judicata is that their courts will determine, whether, in appearing in a proceeding in a foreign court, the English National appearing, was put on notice by the local law that he was subjecting himself to the judgment, which is now produced against him.","start":2011.712,"stop":2032.029,"duration":20.32}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if -- let's assume now that they looked at it and said they were right.","start":2032.029,"stop":2036.703,"duration":4.67},{"text":"They knew it and they went in there with that knowledge.","start":2036.703,"stop":2040.787,"duration":4.08},{"text":"Do you -- is it your position that you've looked into it that the British courts would accept it as res judicata then?","start":2040.787,"stop":2049.188,"duration":8.4}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"No, if -- if you mean they would accept your decision in this Court after this --","start":2049.188,"stop":2053.072,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, as to the amount.","start":2053.072,"stop":2054.851,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"No, they would not accept the judgment as to the amount.","start":2054.851,"stop":2059.341,"duration":4.49},{"text":"And I think even if this Court should decide that a suit did lie, they would say, “From now on, this is the law of the United States, it's perfectly clear.","start":2059.341,"stop":2068.397,"duration":9.06},{"text":"Anyone who goes in now into a limitation of liability is on notice.”","start":2068.397,"stop":2072.944,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And they would accept it there?","start":2072.944,"stop":2074.67,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"I doubt they would but not now, not -- not in the presence of it.","start":2074.67,"stop":2081.505,"duration":6.84},{"text":"Now that we come to the second question, which the Court --","start":2081.505,"stop":2084.393,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the monition would involve a complete submission of every possible vulnerable claim after this had become clearly the law of the United States.","start":2084.393,"stop":2096.518,"duration":12.13}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that's what the --","start":2096.518,"stop":2097.161,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what the monition then would mean.","start":2097.161,"stop":2098.747,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That would mean, but the monition --","start":2098.747,"stop":2099.664,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What you're saying the monition now means, you go in to litigate the limitation fault and the limitation of that fund.","start":2099.664,"stop":2106.683,"duration":7.02}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's what it says and those were precise words, Your Honor.","start":2106.683,"stop":2109.816,"duration":3.13},{"text":"That it says, “You are summoned to appear in the United States District Court in the City of Norfolk, et cetera, to litigate or to object to, if you wish, the question of the liability of the United States and the amount of your claim against the United States.","start":2109.816,"stop":2125.396,"duration":15.58},{"text":"Now, that's all that it says in this monition.","start":2125.396,"stop":2128.082,"duration":2.69},{"text":"And that's all that the statute says at the same road.","start":2128.082,"stop":2131.373,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose there's no British decision on this face of the law you're speaking out here.You're -- you're making a conjecture on the basis of what practice has been.","start":2131.373,"stop":2142.278,"duration":10.9}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm -- I'm making a conjectural argument, Your Honor, so far as this case is concerned, but there are many British decisions on the principle which I'm arguing.","start":2142.278,"stop":2153.525,"duration":11.25},{"text":"And that principle is, did the person who is now faced with the judgment, have noticed when he went into the foreign court that this issue would be litigated?","start":2153.525,"stop":2164.207,"duration":10.68},{"text":"And if he did, the courts of England say, “Well, you've got to abide by it,” but if it was a surprise to him and this happens very often in the English courts between the continent in England, then they will retry the issue.","start":2164.207,"stop":2176.412,"duration":12.2}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"There are cases of that kind, Mr. Acheson?","start":2176.412,"stop":2179.12,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg you pardon.","start":2179.12,"stop":2179.446,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"You said there are English cases of that kind.","start":2179.446,"stop":2182.379,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"There are English cases of that kind, not on this statute, Justice Whittaker, but there are of the kind that I would say and they're cited in our brief.","start":2182.379,"stop":2191.598,"duration":9.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But your -- your -- or the proper construction of Rule 56 -- correct me if I'm wrong, the proper construction for which you contend is not restricted to claims or appearances by foreign vessels.","start":2191.598,"stop":2209.017,"duration":17.42},{"text":"It would apply, as it's an American vessel, would it not?","start":2209.017,"stop":2212.117,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it is.","start":2212.117,"stop":2212.749,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You're construing the general statute, which is not restricted to the appearance of foreign ships.","start":2212.749,"stop":2217.097,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes I am Your Honor, yes.","start":2217.097,"stop":2218.971,"duration":1.87},{"text":"You're quire right.","start":2218.971,"stop":2220.808,"duration":1.84},{"text":"Now, the -- the Court of Appeals found another reason for overruling the District Court, reversing the District Court.","start":2220.808,"stop":2227.579,"duration":6.77},{"text":"And -- and this was on the analogy of equity receivership proceedings, particularly, the case of Alexander versus Hillman.","start":2227.579,"stop":2236.937,"duration":9.36},{"text":"Now, it would always seem to me that the most confusing mental exercise, which one can indulge, is analogy.","start":2236.937,"stop":2243.795,"duration":6.86},{"text":"That always makes these people up, because they get the wrong analogy.","start":2243.795,"stop":2248.08,"duration":4.28},{"text":"Instead of thinking about the problem, they're thinking about some other problem.","start":2248.08,"stop":2252.074,"duration":3.99},{"text":"And here, the Court got on to equity receivership.","start":2252.074,"stop":2256.166,"duration":4.09},{"text":"That it misunderstood what went on in equity receivership.","start":2256.166,"stop":2259.123,"duration":2.96},{"text":"And then, applying an analogy wrongly, it came to a wrong conclusion.","start":2259.123,"stop":2264.292,"duration":5.17},{"text":"The case of Alexander versus Hillman is one of insolvent to state, an out-of-state creditor appearing, to make a demand against the estate, but withholding from the estate, property of the insolvent in the hands of the claimant.","start":2264.292,"stop":2282.431,"duration":18.14},{"text":"And this Court said, “You can't do that.","start":2282.431,"stop":2285.233,"duration":2.8},{"text":"If you come in here to litigate your relations with this estate, we're going to litigate them all.","start":2285.233,"stop":2290.913,"duration":5.68},{"text":"We're not going to just litigate to what you want to litigate.”","start":2290.913,"stop":2294.577,"duration":3.66},{"text":"And the Court said, “On behalf of creditors and stockholders, the receivers reasonably may insist, that before taking part, respondents made by the receivership court to be required to make restitution.”","start":2294.577,"stop":2307.557,"duration":12.98},{"text":"Well that's clear.","start":2307.557,"stop":2309.622,"duration":2.07},{"text":"The distribution, it went on, may not be made without decision on the counterclaims.","start":2309.622,"stop":2315.026,"duration":5.4},{"text":"Nothing is more clearly apart of the subject matter of the main suit, than recovery of all but to the res belongs.","start":2315.026,"stop":2322.619,"duration":7.59},{"text":"Now, that's perfectly clear.","start":2322.619,"stop":2324.844,"duration":2.22},{"text":"But in this case, the main suit is the liability of the United States.","start":2324.844,"stop":2329.936,"duration":5.09},{"text":"The res in the hands of the Court, if it were not for the sovereignty of the United States, would be the value of the Haiti Victory.","start":2329.936,"stop":2338.059,"duration":8.12},{"text":"It's not only possible but it's necessary to determine the main suit and to distribute that res without confusing this, by side issues brought in by claims of claimants with one another.","start":2338.059,"stop":2349.634,"duration":11.57}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Acheson, a non-bearing question, but do you draw a distinction between the asserted claim that you say is not here in the United States against the Duke of York, which they've tried to assert in this proceeding?","start":2349.634,"stop":2367.798,"duration":18.16},{"text":"And the claimant said, “Being sought to be asserted against the Duke of York by co-claimants.”","start":2367.798,"stop":2373.319,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- these are different questions.","start":2373.319,"stop":2375.312,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Different questions.","start":2375.312,"stop":2376.309,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"They stem really from the same main consideration, which is, did the British Transport Commission would come present in the United States for all the litigation, which might grow up of this collision?","start":2376.309,"stop":2388.826,"duration":12.52},{"text":"That's the basic fact, but the rights of claimants against one another are somewhat different from the rights of the petitioner against the claimants, not very, but someone.","start":2388.826,"stop":2397.25,"duration":8.42}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You'd say that it would -- you'd say that it might be that the United States could cross-claim in effect your offset against the -- against the Duke of York, but it doesn't follow us on that, that a claimant, it exposes himself to a claim of procurement.","start":2397.25,"stop":2411.274,"duration":14.02}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I -- I wouldn't admit that premise, but I would --","start":2411.274,"stop":2414.561,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I wouldn't think you would.","start":2414.561,"stop":2415.146,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"-- enthusiast to digress the conclusion.[Laughter]","start":2415.146,"stop":2419.849,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm wondering whether there is a distinction between the two of them.","start":2419.849,"stop":2422.913,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I think there is some -- some distinction, yes, Justice Harlan.","start":2422.913,"stop":2428.101,"duration":5.19},{"text":"Now, the -- the foreign law looks at the matter the way we -- we look at it.","start":2428.101,"stop":2434.354,"duration":6.25},{"text":"Can the law of all the, well, western maritime countries, Canada, England, France, Italy, Spain, Belgium, the Netherlands, all the Scandinavian countries.","start":2434.354,"stop":2445.684,"duration":11.33},{"text":"Claimants in an admiralty proceeding cannot litigate issues inter se.","start":2445.684,"stop":2452.518,"duration":6.83},{"text":"Now, the Government says, “Well, do you -- you don't really frankly state what the foreign law is, because they say in the foreign law,” that is the continent, this isn't true of Canada, “but to some extent, in England and on the continent, liability of the shipowner must be determined before you begin the question of how much shall be given to what claimants.”","start":2452.518,"stop":2477.092,"duration":24.57},{"text":"And the limitation proceeding which is the second one, does not have questions of liability involved in it.","start":2477.092,"stop":2484.18,"duration":7.09},{"text":"And so, the United States has well, of course -- of course, there are claims between claimants here, because all of that was settled in the original proceeding.","start":2484.18,"stop":2494.476,"duration":10.3},{"text":"Well, what we say is you misunderstood it.","start":2494.476,"stop":2496.6,"duration":2.12},{"text":"We -- we are talking about the whole business as one proceeding.","start":2496.6,"stop":2501.954,"duration":5.35},{"text":"Surely, they have different docket numbers.","start":2501.954,"stop":2503.647,"duration":1.69},{"text":"They have different title numbers.","start":2503.647,"stop":2505.614,"duration":1.97},{"text":"But the foreign courts decide the question of liability first just as we do in the limitation proceeding.","start":2505.614,"stop":2511.72,"duration":6.11},{"text":"And when we say, “Is it none of these countries at anytime in admiralty make claimants claim against one another?”","start":2511.72,"stop":2519.754,"duration":8.03},{"text":"They simple aren't permitted to do so.","start":2519.754,"stop":2522.451,"duration":2.7},{"text":"And in fact, in only two countries may a shipowner proceeded against, even put out a settlor against the claimant, and that is in the Netherlands and that is in France.","start":2522.451,"stop":2536.798,"duration":14.35},{"text":"Now, Your Honors --","start":2536.798,"stop":2537.076,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Different statute or accepted admiralty law?","start":2537.076,"stop":2540.334,"duration":3.26}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That's by accepted procedure, not by a statute.","start":2540.334,"stop":2543.487,"duration":3.15},{"text":"It's just never has occurred under the civil law of France and the Netherlands are deeply criticized, Your Honor, for permitting this.","start":2543.487,"stop":2551.898,"duration":8.41},{"text":"Now, against this record of a 100 years, let me briefly speak of some cases which the Government brings up.","start":2551.898,"stop":2560.493,"duration":8.59},{"text":"The Government's argument is that admiralty is so flexible that whatever the rules say, this Court would be permitting.","start":2560.493,"stop":2568.852,"duration":8.36},{"text":"In fact, the Government regards words as so genially compliant as to warrant the most remarkable results from using them.","start":2568.852,"stop":2578.197,"duration":9.35},{"text":"On page 15 of their brief, they have this sentence.","start":2578.197,"stop":2581.873,"duration":3.68},{"text":"It says, “Allowance of cross-claims between co-parties has been a characteristic feature of the limitation concourse since its inception.”","start":2581.873,"stop":2592.22,"duration":10.35},{"text":"Now, that would certainly seem to carry to the unsuspected mind that this had been a pretty characteristic proceeding for, well, over a century.","start":2592.22,"stop":2602.397,"duration":10.18},{"text":"Curious, if that is so, that both the courts below thought it was a case of first impression and that the co-respondents in this case also think it's a case of first impression.","start":2602.397,"stop":2613.527,"duration":11.13},{"text":"However, one finds on reading further in the Government's brief that they don't mean what they say at all, but they do mean, is that in libel actions, where a shipowner libels another shipowner, and that shipowner in turn libels back, that in those proceedings, each shipowner is entitled to limitation.","start":2613.527,"stop":2634.553,"duration":21.03},{"text":"Well, of course, he is.","start":2634.553,"stop":2635.435,"duration":0.88},{"text":"Nobody has ever suggested that he wouldn't be.","start":2635.435,"stop":2637.703,"duration":2.27},{"text":"Limitation is a defense, whether it be a libel or a cross-libel or however it is, maybe, you're entitled to that defense.","start":2637.703,"stop":2645.265,"duration":7.56},{"text":"But it certainly is not the case.","start":2645.265,"stop":2647.366,"duration":2.1},{"text":"In fact, the exact composite is the case, that allowance of cross-claims between co-parties has been the characteristic feature of limitation procedures in section.","start":2647.366,"stop":2657.497,"duration":10.13},{"text":"Nothing could be informed erroneous than that.","start":2657.497,"stop":2661.536,"duration":4.04},{"text":"And the case is which it gathers together, asserting that admiralty must be very broadly and broadly administered.","start":2661.536,"stop":2670.142,"duration":8.61},{"text":"Our cases, which have nothing to do, were the problem before us.","start":2670.142,"stop":2673.906,"duration":3.76},{"text":"For instance, in the Scotland, what was the Scotland about?","start":2673.906,"stop":2678.393,"duration":4.49},{"text":"That was a case, which said the foreign shipowners are entitled for limitation proceedings just as much as American shipowners, well, of course.","start":2678.393,"stop":2686.947,"duration":8.55},{"text":"The North Star is a case, which holds, that where two ships are equally liable, each ship is entitled to limitation.","start":2686.947,"stop":2695.32,"duration":8.37},{"text":"Well, surely, it is.","start":2695.32,"stop":2697.592,"duration":2.27},{"text":"The Epsilon, which they cited, it's a case, which says, “Limitation is available for personal injuries as well as injuries to the ship.”","start":2697.592,"stop":2706.396,"duration":8.8},{"text":"The Adah, a great deal of talk about the Adah in the Governments brief, that is authority for the proposition which I've been insisting upon here, which is, that all parties to the limitation proceeding avowed from the question of fault, just as the Commission is bound here.","start":2706.396,"stop":2726.081,"duration":19.68},{"text":"And so, we go along, finding no cases, which support the Government's argument until we come to two, that they think there are two, the City of Boston and the Eastern Dredging case.","start":2726.081,"stop":2738.665,"duration":12.58},{"text":"Now, these are not two cases, they're one case.","start":2738.665,"stop":2740.891,"duration":2.23},{"text":"They're in 1909.","start":2740.891,"stop":2743.097,"duration":2.21},{"text":"They were both in the same District Court in Massachusetts.","start":2743.097,"stop":2746.762,"duration":3.66},{"text":"They did not grow out.","start":2746.762,"stop":2747.848,"duration":1.09},{"text":"It was very earthshaking, a maritime disaster.","start":2747.848,"stop":2751.279,"duration":3.43},{"text":"The ferryboat, in the City of Boston, and Boston harbor run into a scow and did not hurt the scow at all.","start":2751.279,"stop":2755.927,"duration":4.65},{"text":"It didn't hurt itself much, but that Mr. and Mrs. Davenport fell overboard and they were rescued, a good deal of outrage by the performance, but not much the worst way.","start":2755.927,"stop":2770.943,"duration":15.02},{"text":"Both shipowners started limitation proceedings in the same court in Boston.","start":2770.943,"stop":2776.404,"duration":5.46},{"text":"The Ferry Company went into the Dredging Company's limitation preceding and filed a claim, the sum of $4000 just to call us to fix up the ferryboat.","start":2776.404,"stop":2785.42,"duration":9.02},{"text":"Mr. and Mrs. Davenport went into the ferryboat's proceeding but not into the scow, and they claimed $3500 for their experience in the water.","start":2785.42,"stop":2795.113,"duration":9.69},{"text":"Judge Dodge thought this over and the problem was, of course, how did both ships we're held equally at fault?","start":2795.113,"stop":2801.3,"duration":6.19},{"text":"How he get the Davenport damages equally divided when they were claiming in one preceding but not in the other.","start":2801.3,"stop":2808.279,"duration":6.98},{"text":"So, first of all, he made a mistake.","start":2808.279,"stop":2810.834,"duration":2.55},{"text":"The report on page 171 of 182 F., he held that it to bring the scow into the ferryboat's proceeding.","start":2810.834,"stop":2821.178,"duration":10.34},{"text":"This is cited by the United States.","start":2821.178,"stop":2823.735,"duration":2.56},{"text":"However, on page 179, he did change his mind on that, and thought that wasn't a very good procedure.","start":2823.735,"stop":2830.187,"duration":6.45},{"text":"And the best thing to do is to allow the Ferry Company, which was in the Scow Company's proceeding to put one-half of the Davenport's judgment onto its claim, which they did.","start":2830.187,"stop":2840.456,"duration":10.27},{"text":"So, you see, nobody was brought in under Rule 56 and made pay anything.","start":2840.456,"stop":2847.018,"duration":6.56},{"text":"The same thing turns out to be the case of -- of that long litigation between the United States and the Steel Products Company, which grew out of the accident on the Pacific Maneuvers of 1920.","start":2847.018,"stop":2860.663,"duration":13.64},{"text":"There, the steel inventor, a ship of the Steel Products Company, had got into the middle of the destroyer formation on night, and ran into and sank the USS Destroyer Woolsey, making a total loss of it.","start":2860.663,"stop":2876.312,"duration":15.65},{"text":"There were several hearings that were all cited here, except the last part, which should be.","start":2876.312,"stop":2882.563,"duration":6.25},{"text":"The first point was two cargo owners, owners of cargo on the Steel Inventor, who were prevented by the Harter Act from suing the Steel Inventor went into the limitation of liability proceedings started by the Steel Inventor, and said, “We cannot sue the Steel Inventor.","start":2882.563,"stop":2900.846,"duration":18.28},{"text":"We can't sue the United States because it's sovereign.","start":2900.846,"stop":2904.253,"duration":3.41},{"text":"But if the Steel Inventor is held at fault, it's going to be a big fund in the Court and we want our share of it.\"","start":2904.253,"stop":2911.533,"duration":7.28},{"text":"And after some discussion, it was decided very well, “You can file your claims against this fund, not against United States, it's the sovereign.","start":2911.533,"stop":2920.594,"duration":9.06},{"text":"But before the United States gets the money, maybe you can get hold of some of it.”","start":2920.594,"stop":2927.8,"duration":7.21},{"text":"This is said to be a cross-claim.","start":2927.8,"stop":2931.099,"duration":3.3},{"text":"It wasn't a cross-claim.","start":2931.099,"stop":2932.291,"duration":1.19},{"text":"It was a claim on the fund in the hands of the Court.","start":2932.291,"stop":2934.899,"duration":2.61},{"text":"But furthermore, nothing came of it, because it was decided that the Woolsey was at fault and not the Steel Inventors, so the whole litigation evaporated.","start":2934.899,"stop":2944.061,"duration":9.16},{"text":"Then, there was another part of the litigation, which is much more interesting, and that was that the United States came into the Steel Inventor's proceeding with a claim, whereupon, the Steel Products Company, filed a cross-libel against the United States.","start":2944.061,"stop":2962.305,"duration":18.24},{"text":"And Judge Hough said, “You can't do that.","start":2962.305,"stop":2965.336,"duration":3.03},{"text":"That can't be done.”","start":2965.336,"stop":2967.837,"duration":2.5},{"text":"Because he says, “This does raise the question of an affirmative claim against the claimant in a limitation proceeding.”","start":2967.837,"stop":2974.899,"duration":7.06},{"text":"And he should -- the argument here is that every claimant who answers and opposes limitation is a libel, and therefore, is subject to a cross-libel.","start":2974.899,"stop":2988.698,"duration":13.8},{"text":"But he says, “That isn't so.”","start":2988.698,"stop":2990.894,"duration":2.2},{"text":"“A libel,” said Judge Hough, “is a statement of claim on which process may issue.","start":2990.894,"stop":2997.119,"duration":6.23},{"text":"No process issues on an answer.”","start":2997.119,"stop":3000.756,"duration":3.64},{"text":"“A libel must state damage.”","start":3000.756,"stop":3002.685,"duration":1.93},{"text":"But he claimed, “It does not have to state any damage.","start":3002.685,"stop":3004.881,"duration":2.2},{"text":"All that it states is that a claim is put in.”","start":3004.881,"stop":3008.219,"duration":3.34},{"text":"Three a libel is the beginning of an action.","start":3008.219,"stop":3011.118,"duration":2.9},{"text":"The answer is not the beginning of an action.","start":3011.118,"stop":3013.771,"duration":2.65},{"text":"Now, he says, “Surely, this is technical.”","start":3013.771,"stop":3016.461,"duration":2.69},{"text":"And then, this sentence, which I -- I venture to quote to the Court, “These technicalities are not unimportant.","start":3016.461,"stop":3024.659,"duration":8.2},{"text":"For while there could be a theory of law without any applied technique, there can be no application thereof without some technique, which lies at the very foundation of legal application.”","start":3024.659,"stop":3038.517,"duration":13.86},{"text":"And so, he said, “There cannot be a cross-libel in a limitation proceeding.”","start":3038.517,"stop":3044.919,"duration":6.4},{"text":"Now, counsel criticized this opinion, and I think --","start":3044.919,"stop":3048.659,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what was the name of that case?","start":3048.659,"stop":3049.334,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"-- they do it rather harshly because --","start":3049.334,"stop":3051.011,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the name of that decision?","start":3051.011,"stop":3052.479,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"This is the Steel Inventor.","start":3052.479,"stop":3055.903,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Wasn't that a recent decision?","start":3055.903,"stop":3058.34,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3058.34,"stop":3058.632,"duration":0.29},{"text":"That is the recent one, Your Honor.","start":3058.632,"stop":3059.985,"duration":1.35},{"text":"That was in 1921.","start":3059.985,"stop":3062.09,"duration":2.11},{"text":"The recent one is the Moore-McCormack decision.","start":3062.09,"stop":3067.092,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"But then, the Government says, “Well, Judge Hough didn't cite any -- any authorities.”","start":3067.092,"stop":3072.769,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Judge Hough was agreeing with the Government.","start":3072.769,"stop":3075.337,"duration":2.57},{"text":"The Government was presenting to Judge Hough the argument, which I am now presenting to you.","start":3075.337,"stop":3080.366,"duration":5.03},{"text":"And at that time, there were no authorities or clearly, the Government would've found them.","start":3080.366,"stop":3085.664,"duration":5.3},{"text":"But they thought --","start":3085.664,"stop":3086.29,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you invoke the fact to Judge Hough?","start":3086.29,"stop":3088.263,"duration":1.97},{"text":"I haven't read the opinion.","start":3088.263,"stop":3089.16,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":3089.16,"stop":3089.533,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he -- did Judge Hough invoked the practice?","start":3089.533,"stop":3092.576,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Practice?","start":3092.576,"stop":3093.304,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3093.304,"stop":3093.68,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3093.68,"stop":3094.598,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Because even the good deal of a car did himself.","start":3094.598,"stop":3097.233,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Very considerable authority, Your Honor, very great authority.","start":3097.233,"stop":3102.031,"duration":4.8},{"text":"But the Government says, “Judge Hough was reversed by the Court of Appeals,” and that we, in our brief, did not mention that, and it points out how unfortunate that was.","start":3102.031,"stop":3113.089,"duration":11.06},{"text":"It would indeed have been unfortunate if it had occurred.","start":3113.089,"stop":3116.828,"duration":3.74},{"text":"But unfortunately, there is still another decision, which the Government didn't come across.","start":3116.828,"stop":3122.449,"duration":5.62},{"text":"And in that decision, the Court of Appeals found as I say, that the Woolsey was solely at fault.","start":3122.449,"stop":3130.199,"duration":7.75},{"text":"Therefore, it ends up its -- it's true.","start":3130.199,"stop":3133.303,"duration":3.1},{"text":"It disagreed with Judge Hough.","start":3133.303,"stop":3134.957,"duration":1.65},{"text":"It said, “Well, we want him to decide on this one.”","start":3134.957,"stop":3137.173,"duration":2.22},{"text":"But it ends up its decision by saying, “In view of our decision as to liability, all other questions raised on this appeal are moot.”","start":3137.173,"stop":3147.345,"duration":10.17},{"text":"So, this Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit was saved from error by mootness on that point.","start":3147.345,"stop":3155.381,"duration":8.04},{"text":"The Court of Appeals is, I hope, going to be saved from error again by this Court.","start":3155.381,"stop":3162.764,"duration":7.38},{"text":"In Moore-McCormack, it decided that the claimants could file claims against a co-claimant.","start":3162.764,"stop":3174.424,"duration":11.66},{"text":"That, however, was an interlocutory decision.","start":3174.424,"stop":3177.415,"duration":2.99},{"text":"The case is now at trial.","start":3177.415,"stop":3180.254,"duration":2.84},{"text":"And so, we believe that before it reaches the point where the Court may I have to commit error, Your Honors will have saved them from doing so.","start":3180.254,"stop":3189.811,"duration":9.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you mind telling what these citations of Judge Hough's opinion?","start":3189.811,"stop":3192.7,"duration":2.89},{"text":"Is that the -- the matter of the Court?","start":3192.7,"stop":3195.054,"duration":2.35},{"text":"Is that the --","start":3195.054,"stop":3195.946,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"That's --","start":3195.946,"stop":3196.488,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- 1925 A.M.C.?","start":3196.488,"stop":3197.786,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":3197.786,"stop":3198.469,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":3198.469,"stop":3198.733,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"It's 19 --","start":3198.733,"stop":3200.147,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"1924, all right.","start":3200.147,"stop":3201.054,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"1925 American Maritime --","start":3201.054,"stop":3203.041,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Evidently, it's not in the federal report.","start":3203.041,"stop":3205.597,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"Dean G. Acheson","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not.","start":3205.597,"stop":3212.75,"duration":7.15},{"text":"There is one other decision, which they cite, which had the same fate, The Clio and The Springhill.","start":3212.75,"stop":3219.544,"duration":6.79},{"text":"There, there was an intervention permitted under Rule 56, not an intervention, but of bringing in of the shipowner into another shipowner's limitation of liability proceeding.","start":3219.544,"stop":3231.326,"duration":11.78},{"text":"But there again, the fault was found on the ship who brought in the third party, and therefore, that again evaporated.","start":3231.326,"stop":3240.451,"duration":9.13},{"text":"So, I end up as I begin, Your Honors, by saying that in the whole 106 years of practice under this statute, there has not been one single case where a dollar has been recovered from the claimant in the limitation of liability proceeding.","start":3240.451,"stop":3265.854,"duration":25.4}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Apr 29, 1957","petitioner":"British Transport Commission","respondent":"United States","docket":"247","citation":"354 US 129 (1957)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/354/129","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 10, 1957"}